1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Be7 {A very solid approach; typically, when people get surprised, they make solid moves, and ... Be7 looks very natural.} 5. Bd3 {This is an awkward-looking move, but it is actually quite a good one. The idea is to play c3 , Bc2 , and prepare d2 - d4 .} O-O 6. c3 d6 7. Bc2 {Right now we give Black the opportunity to take on d5 and to try to create a strong center by playing ... f5 later on.} Be6 {This move has occurred three times already, and I can surely say that this is the most natural move in this position. Black is forcing the white knight to make a decision.} 8. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {The right way to take on e7 ; now Black wants to play ... d5 and take the center.} 9. O-O d5 10. d4 ({Funnily enough, I do have a game here as well, and I did not play the right move. I went} 10. d3 {, which is passive, but since you are studying this course, you will hopefully play better than me. :)}) 10... exd4 {This is the reason why I did not like d4 ; ... exd4 really does look good for Black.} (10... dxe4 11. Nxe5 {and we do have the bishop pair advantage; Bg5 as well as f4 are good moves to be prepared to make when the time is right. Black lacks a viable way to equalize the position.}) 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nxd4 {This is a difficult move to play if you are unaware of it, as it is hard to understand at first why White sacrifices the pawn, but it actually leads to a very straightforward game.} (12. cxd4 {is the move that I was analyzing during my own game, and I thought it wasn't good, and the reason was} Bg4 {. The pin is annoying, our d4 -pawn is hanging, and ... f6 is very strong as well, so this is not an ideal position to be in as White.}) 12... Nxe5 13. f3 Nf6 14. Re1 Nc6 {Every other move would be faced with f4 - f5 .} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qd4 {A very strong move; the idea is to transfer the queen to h4 and bring the bishop to g5 .} Rfe8 (16... c5 17. Qh4 Rfe8 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bxh6 gxh6 20. Qxh6 {is a good example of what we are trying to achieve. Black must keep the knight on f6 to make sure that they will not get mated, while Re5 - g5 is unstoppable.}) 17. Qh4 {This is the best move. We want to go Qh4 followed up by Bg5 , and after ... h6 , every single time we would sacrifice our bishop on h6 , the attack will be very strong and unstoppable.} *

