1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Nxe4 5. d4 {I recommend another pawn sacrifice, with the main idea of opening up the position with tempo and trying to create dynamic and active play.} exd4 ({We have now transposed to the Belgrade Gambit, having avoided some alternatives that Black has after} 5... exd4 {exd4 Nd5 .}) 6. Bd3 {Yes, we did indeed sacrifice two central pawns to get ahead in development; Bd3 is a good move, and activating a piece with tempo is always good.} Nf6 {Although this is also an option, I believe that in practice it will lead to a worse outcome for Black.} 7. Qe2+ {It’s important to remember to make this move and not to play Bg5 instead.} Be7 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 9. Bh6 {The whole point of this outcome was to make sure that we would spoil Black's pawn structure so that they would be unable to castle short.} d5 10. O-O-O a6 {The only and strongest move, with the idea to stop Bb5 . This is a very deep move, and one must be a very strong player to find it.} (10... Be6 {is the most natural reaction, which leads to a losing position.} 11. Bb5 {and on the next move, White will capture the d4 -pawn with the knight, when Black will be unable to castle on any side of the board, and that would lead to a disaster.}) 11. Nh4 {This is a very nice move; the idea is to play f4 and also to remain open to the idea of Bf5 .} Be6 12. f4 {Our ideas are simple: we should do everything to stop ... O-O-O ; right now, ... Qd7 is not an option because of f5 and the bishop is trapped, and in case of other moves, either Rhe1 or Rde1 is always very logical and helpful to play.} Qd6 {This is by far the most natural move. Black aims to castle long.} 13. Nf5 {Now Ng7 + needs to be stopped.} Bxf5 14. Bxf5 {The black king is going to stay in the center for the rest of the game, and the position, despite being two pawns up, is almost lost. Our ideas are quite simple: we bring the last piece to the game with Rhe1 , and on our next move, we try to attack with ideas such as Rd3 - b3 or Rd3 - g3 , and there’s nothing much that Black can do here.} *

