1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Nd7 {This is the main move in this position; it is very ambitious and leads to heavily theoretical lines.} (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. O-O a6 5. Bxd7+ ({The main move here is} 5. Bd3 {, but we are looking for a different type of game, where we give away the bishop pair for activity.}) 5... Bxd7 6. c3 {The idea, once again, is very obvious. White wants to take the center with d2 - d4 .} Nf6 ({Other moves, such as} 6... e6 {or g6 , won't stop our} 7. d4 {expansion plans.}) 7. Re1 e6 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 {This is a very common way to meet the c3 and d4 plan.} (9... Be7 {is very popular but not ambitious; it allows White to take full control over the center and have comfortable play.} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bf4 {, and now that White has a firm grip in the center, our plan is quite straightforward: Qd2 and Rad1 , with the idea to push either e5 or d5 .}) 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nfd2 ({The difference between Nfd2 and Nbd2 is that after} 11. Nbd2 {,} Bc6 {is very strong and solid. Following} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 Bb4 {, White's pieces end up slightly offside while Black can quickly castle and increase the pressure on the d4 -pawn.}) 11... Nxd2 ({Pinning the knight with} 11... Bb4 {fails immediately to either} 12. Qg4 {or Nxe4 since Bxe1 is met by the intermediate} Nd6 {.}) 12. Nxd2 Be7 13. Re3 {It is very important to understand that White should play very actively, and Re3 is the best way to do it right now, launching an attack immediately.} O-O 14. Rg3 {White is better. The next move is Qg4 , forcing Black to play ... g6 , and after Nf3 , White will control all the dark squares.} Rc8 15. Qg4 g6 16. Nf3 {White is positionally winning; Bg5 is an idea to trade the dark-squared bishops and make the dark squares even weaker, or Qf4 with the idea of Qh6 and Rh3 .} *

