1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... e6 {This is probably one of the oldest approaches in chess history, and it leads to many theoretical discussions such as the Paulsen or Taimanov.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {This is an extremely rare idea, and a very strange-looking one as well. The point is to keep the knight on f3 and place the queen on e3 after ... Nc6 .} Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Nc3 {This is the main position of this line. Here Black has many options, and we are going to react to each of these options in different ways.} Bb4 {The most natural approach, pinning the knight, with the idea of pushing ... d7 - d5 .} 7. a3 (7. a3 {is more restrictive than Bd2 , which would give Black the extra option of} d6 {. After a3 Bc5} 8. Qg5 h6 9. Qg3 {( Qxg7? Bxf2+ Kxf2} Rg8 {and White has a big problem with the queen.) Nh5} 10. Qh3 {Nf6 , White has to tread carefully given Black's ... e5 idea, which is another upside of 7...d6 .} ({If we follow the same variation but with a3 instead, after Ba5} 10. Bd2 {Bb6 Qg5 h6 Qg3} Nh5 11. Qh3 Nf6 {, White has} 12. e5 {with a nearly winning position.})) 7... Ba5 8. Bd2 {A logical move, stopping the annoying pin, and preparing e4 - e5 .} O-O 9. e5 Bxc3 {A strong intermezzo, eliminating the c3 -knight in order to get the d5 -square for the black knight.} 10. Qxc3 Ne4 {Black has to try to trade the knight for the bishop, as otherwise, White would be left with two bishops.} 11. Qe3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 {For the moment, White has the strong e5 -pawn, which keeps the c8 -bishop out of the game.} f6 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. O-O-O {It is very safe to castle queenside; the idea for now is to put the queen on the d6 -square and stop the development of Black's pieces.} d5 {The idea here for Black is simple, yet very dangerous. Black is aiming to put the rook on d8 , protecting the d5 -pawn, push ... e5 , and take full control of the center.} 15. Bb5 {The purpose of this move is very simple: it is a developing move; Rhe1 is coming next, and after that Black will never be able to control the center.} a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qe3 {White is controlling the e5 -square, and after Rd2 , Re1 , and Ne5 , White will have a dominating position.} ({After Rb8 , we can calmly defend with} 17. c3 {, not worrying about 'weakening' the light squares since Black has no way to take advantage of that. Next, we can play Rd2 , defending the pawn on f2 and preparing the knight jump to e5 with or without the inclusion of Re1 , depending on the circumstances. White is better.}) *

