1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e5 {Lately, this has gained a lot of popularity; the idea is to bring the bishop to d6 and the knight to e7 .} 4. O-O Bd6 5. d3 {A tricky move, with the idea to keep the c3 -square for the knight. We do not try to make c3 - d4 work. Instead, we are trying to play Nc3 and Bc4 to take control over the d5 -square.} Nge7 {After ... Nge7 , we no longer opt for Bg5 since Black has many options: ... O-O and ... f6 , or ... h6 immediately, when we don't want to take on e7 ; if the knight is on f6 , then after ... h6 , Bxf6 and ... Qxf6 , the hole on d5 would become more prominent, and Black would have clumsier pieces.  Moreover, after ... Nge7 , the kingside is slightly neglected leaving room for the queen to potentially enter the game via h5 , while the knight can eye both the h4 and g5 -squares.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bc4 {We want to go Ng5 and Qh5 if Black allows us to do that.} Bc7 ({After} 7... h6 8. Nh4 Bc7 9. Qh5 {, Bh6 and f4 are coming. The position is hopeless for Black.}) 8. Ng5 h6 {The only way to stop Qh5 .} 9. Qh5 {We play it anyway!} hxg5 10. Bxg5 {Now White has multiple ideas: one is to bring the rook to h3 , which can be done with Rae1 - e3 or f4 followed by Rf3 ; another idea is to play Nd5 - f6 +, and that would lead to a checkmate.} Qe8 {The only move to avoid Nd5 .} 11. Rae1 d6 12. f4 exf4 13. Rxf4 {It is impossible for Black to stop Rh4 without major losses.} *

