1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Nc6 {The main idea behind this move is to prepare to castle long.} 5. Bb5 {This is the main move in the position, which leads to a very sharp game.} a6 {A very modern approach, mostly played by the German GM Matthias Bluebaum. The main idea is to force White to capture on c6 , and then later on to prove that Black is able to equalize due to having the bishop pair advantage.} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O Bd6 {Black needs to develop the knight on e7 in order to protect the c6 -pawn, but for that, they need to develop the dark-squared bishop first.} 8. Ne5 {Since Black now has the bishop pair advantage, White needs to take action as soon as possible, and Ne5 is the move that leads to very direct and complex positions.} Ne7 {A very logical move − the idea is to develop slowly, castle short, and push the knight away with ... f6 .} 9. Bg5 {An extremely strong move, with the idea of capturing the c6 -pawn by using the pin.} f6 {It is important to know why this move does not work.} 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qh5+ {Black will get mated after ... Kf8 , and ... Ng6 would bring a hopeless position.} *

