1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Nf6 {In this line, people tend to think White is not very ambitious, so Black is keeping the position symmetrical by making the same moves.} 5. Bd3 Bd6 {Continuing a tendency and simply developing the pieces.} 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 {This is one of the main positions that occurs after 3.exd5 ; h3 is a very prophylactic move: it stops ... Bg4 and after h3 , we are going to start taking action to gain an advantage and change the logic of the game.} h6 {Why not? Definitely, it is very logical to make the same move as we do. And it has been played by the majority of players.} 8. Nc3 {A very strong move; Nb5 is the threat, as we do want to get the bishop pair advantage.} c6 (8... Nc6 {instead allows our bishop pair hunting with} 9. Nb5 {, and after} Nb4 10. Nxd6 Qxd6 11. Bb5 Bf5 12. Ba4 {, we can think about improving our pieces with Ne5 , c3 , Re1 , etc.}) 9. Re1 {Already, we’ve achieved the change of dynamics here, and it does feel as though we are ahead in development. The follow-up ideas are Ne5 , Bf4 , and Qf3 .} Re8 10. Ne5 Nbd7 {In order to prevent White from achieving their goals, Black must challenge the e5 -knight.} 11. Bf4 Qc7 {A very natural and very good-looking move; it does seem as if Black has managed to force White to take on d7 , which would lead to simplifications and most likely the game would end in a draw, but we do have an extremely powerful response here.} 12. Qf3 {A very strong move, setting a very nice trap. If Black does not touch the e5 -knight, we will double our rooks on the e-file and will have full control over the center.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 {The most natural approach, which leads to a losing position for Black.} 14. Rxe5 Rxe5 15. Qg3 Nd7 16. Bxh6 Re1+ {This is the only way to escape the mating attack, but here after some direct moves, White is up material with a winning position.} ({After} 16... g6 17. Bxg6 {, mate is unavoidable.}) 17. Rxe1 Qxg3 18. Re8+ Nf8 19. fxg3 gxh6 20. Bf5 ({White has a winning position after} 20. Bf5 {Rxa8 Bxc2 Ne2+- .}) *

