1. e4 g6 2. d4 ({White continues with} 2. d4 {, reinforcing control over the center. Black's response} Bg7 {signifies the Modern Defense where Black delays pawn moves in favor of flexible piece development.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nf3 {White develops a knight and maintains a strong central presence.} d6 {A very common move in the Modern Defense. Black maintains pawn flexibility for the forthcoming piece development.} 4. Bd3 {This is a reliable move that avoids unnecessary complications and ensures easy play in the middlegame.} Nc6 ({Let's explore a different way for Black to play instead of} 4... Nf6 {. By choosing Nc6 , Black's idea is to keep the option open for playing ... f7 - f5 in the future and also to be able to choose a different square for the other knight.}) 5. c3 e5 6. h3 {Stopping ... Bg4 .} Nge7 {The main idea of developing the knight to e7 is to play ... f5 in the future.} 7. dxe5 {I genuinely very much appreciate this move, as it showcases a solid comprehension of the game. I'm confident that it will indeed make Black's gameplay much more challenging.} Nxe5 ({I believe that} 7... Nxe5 {is a better move than dxe5 , but it does not change our strategy.}) 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 {White is focused on building up the position on the queenside using moves like Be3 , Nd2 , a4 , and b4 . This will help White to take control of that part of the board.} *

