1. e4 g6 2. d4 ({White continues with} 2. d4 {, reinforcing control over the center. Black's response} Bg7 {signifies the Modern Defense where Black delays pawn moves in favor of flexible piece development.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nf3 {White develops a knight and maintains a strong central presence.} d6 {A very common move in the Modern Defense. Black maintains pawn flexibility for the forthcoming piece development.} 4. Bd3 {This is a reliable move that avoids unnecessary complications and ensures easy play in the middlegame.} Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 {Following the steps of 4.Bd3 . This is the main position that I recommend to play against the Pirc Defense, and we are going to take a look at the most common moves here.} c5 {... c5 is a common approach in the Pirc Defense. Black is always trying to hit White's center with moves such as ... c5 and ... e5 .} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. e5 {This approach is very straightforward, providing White with a substantial and robust advantage.} Nd5 9. Be4 Nb6 10. Qe2 {It is better to keep the queens on the board since White has a lot more space.} Nc6 11. Bxc6 {An interesting approach, giving up the bishop pair to damage Black's pawn structure.} bxc6 12. h3 {Keeping all unnecessary complications to a bare minimum after moves like ... Bg4 . Black's pawns on c6 and c5 are extremely weak, and White will always be able to target them with moves like Be3 and Nc3 - e4 ; protecting these pawns will be extremely challenging for Black. The bishop on g7 is also shut out, so neither of the two bishops are very powerful here.} *

