1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 {... Bg4 is a very common move in these types of positions. Black usually tries to give up the pair of bishops and create a solid center with the e6 and c6 -pawns.} 6. h3 Bh5 {It is normally not a good idea to keep the two bishops after ... Bg4 , and this is no exception.} 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 e6 9. Nc4 Qa6 10. h4 {The queen on a6 is badly placed and h5 is unstoppable.} h5 11. Ne5 {Black's position is hopeless.} *

