1. e4 Nf6 (1... Nf6 {, known as Alekhine's Defense, is not the most common move, but it leads to interesting and sharp positions. With Nf6 , Black is provoking White to take the center right from the start of the game.}) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 {We are now at the point when we need to decide whether to play f4 , which leads to a very sharp game, or to play the text move exd6 , which leads to a more positional game.} 5. exd6 exd6 (5... exd6 {is the modern approach, which usually leads to more symmetrical positions.}) 6. Nf3 Be7 7. h3 {In these types of positions, h3 is always a very useful move; it could also be played on move 6, with the main goal of stopping ... Bg4 .} O-O 8. Be2 ({It is interesting to see how White uses} 8. Be2 {. Usually, in these situations, White puts the bishop on d3 . However, Be2 is much easier to play in a faster time control because a bishop on d3 can be attacked with ... Nc6 - b4 and the pawn on d4 is not protected after ... Nc6 and ... Bf6 .}) 8... Bf5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. O-O Bf6 {I think this is the most natural way to play; also, this is the main position that has occurred in the Be2 and h3 line.} 11. g4 (11. g4 {is an extremely strong move; according to the powerful engines, it is the first line. It has never been played before and it is a very forcing line. I believe that it's extremely hard for Black to find the correct moves.}) 11... Bg6 12. g5 Be7 13. d5 Ne5 14. Ne1 Nexc4 {This very natural-looking move is just losing a piece.} 15. a4 {Forcing ... a5 .} a5 16. f4 {Now b3 or f5 is unstoppable.} *

