1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 {There is no clear advantage in the Petroff Defense, which is why I recommend sticking with the Four Knights opening, as it avoids extra theory.} Bb4 ({An interesting move, but in my opinion, very unnecessary. It is the second-best move after} 3... Nc6 {, which is covered through the Nc6 Nc3 Nf6 move order.}) 4. Nxe5 O-O {For the moment, Black does have enough compensation to get the pawn back; it is hard to stop ... Bxc3 and ... Re8 at the same time.} 5. Nd3 {Giving back the pawn for the bishop pair advantage.} Bxc3 6. dxc3 Nxe4 7. Be2 {This is a known position, where White is usually having a risk-free game.} d5 8. O-O c6 9. Re1 {It almost doesn't matter what Black does, I suggest following up with the Bf1 and f3 idea.} Bf5 10. Bf1 Nd7 11. f3 Nef6 12. Be3 {We are going to put the bishop on f2 , Qd2 , and we can also slowly push on both sides of the board, such as a4 - a5 or g4 and h4 .} *

