1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5 {This is a very common move, which is a mistake because it allows us to take control of the center.} 4. Nxe5 {A very nice tactical resource.} Nxe5 (4... Bxf2+ {is obviously way too optimistic, but White should be aware of a small trick down the line} 5. Kxf2 Nxe5 6. d4 Qf6+ 7. Kg1 Ne7 {, and now it is important to leave the knight on e5 intact since grabbing it allows mate in 3. Instead,} 8. h4 {creates luft and we threaten to take on e5 together with an unpleasant Bg5 . Black is lost.}) 5. d4 Bd6 {The only move to not get a losing position immediately.} 6. dxe5 Bxe5 7. Bd3 {White’s game plan is pretty straightforward: finish development with O-O and push f4 .} Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 {Pinning the knight, and after f4 , White’s attack is extremely strong.} *

