1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Be7 {A very solid approach; typically, when people get surprised, they make solid moves, and ... Be7 looks very natural.} 5. Bd3 {This is an awkward-looking move, but it is actually quite a good one. The idea is to play c3 , Bc2 , and prepare d2 - d4 .} O-O 6. c3 d6 7. Bc2 {Right now we give Black the opportunity to take on d5 and to try to create a strong center by playing ... f5 later on.} Nxd5 {Despite the fact that there are no classical encounters reaching this position, I believe that this is a very natural approach.} 8. exd5 Nb8 9. d4 Nd7 {Black needs to keep the e5 -pawn; the trade is meaningless, as then White would have a strong center and all the pieces are active, so Black needs to keep the center and try to strengthen it with ... f5 .} 10. O-O f5 11. dxe5 {Due to having doubled d-pawns, White should not allow ... e4 .} dxe5 12. Qe2 {... Bd6 would allow Ng5 , and ... Bf6 is bad since the f5 -pawn would be hanging, so the most logical move is ... e4 .} e4 13. Nd4 {Now Ne6 is a threat.} Nf6 {It does look like Black has a good position with a good center, and that would be the case if we would play the natural c4 .} 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 {Here the e6 -pawn is extremely strong, and most importantly, Black is unable to take it anytime soon; Bb3 is always an option to defend the pawn. White should always keep an eye on the e6 -pawn, and try to develop and take the d-file.} *

