1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Bc5 {A very natural developing move.} 5. c3 {This already looks dangerous for Black, as d2 - d4 is a threat right now.} Nxe4 {Obviously, we do have to know how to react every time we sacrifice a pawn.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Bd3 {Taking back is not necessary right now, it is much more important to develop the pieces as soon as possible.} Nf6 8. Qe2+ {A typical check, which forces Black to lose the chance to castle and keep the king in a safe position.} Be7 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 d5 12. O-O {White is down a pawn, but Black is unable to castle on either side of the board. Castling short would be very dangerous because of Qh5 ; meanwhile, the c-file is open, which means that castling long would also lead to a very dangerous attack.} *

