1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Bc5 {A very natural developing move.} 5. c3 {This already looks dangerous for Black, as d2 - d4 is a threat right now.} Nxe4 {Obviously, we do have to know how to react every time we sacrifice a pawn.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Bd3 {Taking back is not necessary right now, it is much more important to develop the pieces as soon as possible.} Nf6 8. Qe2+ {A typical check, which forces Black to lose the chance to castle and keep the king in a safe position.} Kf8 9. Nxf6 Qxf6 10. O-O {We do not care about the pawns in this situation for the moment. White needs to play very active right now and Re1 is very strong, with a mating threat.} d6 {The best option to stop Re1 , which will simply be answered with ... Bg4 or ... Be6 and Black will stop our activity.} 11. Bg5 Qe6 12. Qc2 Ne5 {This is also an option. The idea behind this move is to exploit the threat of damaging our pawn structure and creating weaknesses on the kingside. Additionally, by capturing on d3 , Black aims to eliminate our bishop pair advantage.} 13. Nxe5 dxe5 {Now it seems that Black has achieved everything; the center is closed and they are up two pawns, which should be enough to at least equalize the position.} 14. Rae1 {This is a very interesting and potentially dangerous approach, especially in blitz games. Our plan is straightforward: push f4 . This can be followed by Kh1 , and if we manage to open either the e-file or the f-file (or both) , the rooks will become extremely powerful. Meanwhile, Black's king remains vulnerable and stuck in the center.} *

