1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Bc5 {A very natural developing move.} 5. c3 {This already looks dangerous for Black, as d2 - d4 is a threat right now.} O-O 6. d3 {Protecting the e4 -pawn and creating the threat of Bg5 ; b4 is also an idea to keep in mind.} (6. d4 $6 {Tactically, d4 does not work here, but I believe it would be extremely hard for our opponents to find out why it does not work so well in faster time controls.} exd4 7. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 Nxd5 9. exd5 Qh4 10. Be3 {and after many direct and only moves, here as well we have only one move to make, which is Be3 , but unfortunately, after} Re8 {, White is unable to stop both ... Rxe3 and ... Qxd4 or ... Bxd4 at the same time.}) 6... h6 {It is very natural to go ... h6 in order to stop Bg5 .} 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. g4 (8. g4 {is the crux of this line, with the entire point of d3 being to prepare Bg5 and pressure Black into playing ... h6 , allowing the g4 - g5 plan to unfold. As White, we should be pleased after g4 , as it's practically very difficult for Black to stop our attack. The idea behind this move is straightforward: White aims to open the g-file with g4 - g5 , bring the rook to g1 , and launch a mating attack.}) 8... Qd8 9. g5 h5 ({This is the best way for Black to stop the attack.} 9... hxg5 10. Nxg5 {and now Qh5 needs to be stopped. Following} g6 11. h4 {, this is the dream scenario for White to achieve. Opening up the g- and h-files will eventually lead to a mating attack.}) 10. Nh4 g6 11. Bg2 {It is important to stop ... d7 - d5 , and this is also a good developing move, preparing f2 - f4 .} d6 (11... Be7 {is a natural move, attacking the g5 -pawn, which seems to be easy to defend properly. After} 12. Qd2 d6 13. O-O {, White controls the center and has a clear game plan: either push d4 followed by f4 , or the reverse. Black lacks any real counterplay.}) 12. f4 exf4 {Allowing f4 - f5 would be deadly since Black's pieces will be out of the game, and if Black tries to defend the g6 -pawn with ... Kh7 , White can also make Bf3xh5 sacrifices, which would lead to a mating attack.} 13. Bxf4 {White is going to take full control over the center after d3 - d4 , and only after that can White castle short and slowly improve the position with developing moves such as Qd2 and Rae1 .} ({In case of Bg4 , we should avoid the complications that would arise after} 13. Qc2 f6 {since} 14. Nxg6 fxg5 {is too messy. Instead,} 15. Qd2 {prevents f6 , as now we have the strong reply d4 , when fxg5 is well met by the intermediate Bxg5 .}) *

