o prepare Bg5 and pressure Black into playing ... h6 , allowing the g4 - g5 plan to unfold. As White, we should be pleased after g4 , as it's practically very difficult for Black to stop our attack. The idea behind this move is straightforward: White aims to open the g-file with g4 - g5 , bring the rook to g1 , and launch a mating attack.}) 8... Ne7 {This is an extremely tough move to make. The idea behind ... Ne7 is to have ... Qb6 , from where the queen attacks the f2 -pawn, and to bring the knight to g6 , where the knight will defend the king from the attack.} 9. g5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Qb6 {Now Black attacks on f2 and b2 . At the same time, Black is planning to go ... f6 with tempo and ... d5 , taking control over the center.} 11. d4 {Logical and the most aggressive approach.} exd4 12. b4 {It's very important not to capture on d4 immediately since this would allow Black the opportunity to give a check on b4 and push ... d5 , when our attack would be gone and Black would simply exploit the fact that our king is in the center and our pieces are not fully developed yet.} ({So for that reason,} 12. b4 {is forcing Black to go back with the bishop and also keeps the c8 -bishop stuck since ... d7 - d5 is no longer an option.}) 12... Bd6 13. Bc4 dxc3 14. a3 {In this position, the piece activity is much more important than taking pawns. Right now, the threat is to go Rg1 and Bf6 . The attack is extremely dangerous.} *

