1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} d6 {This is the most common move in the position. It is very natural to make a solid move after you face such a new move like 4.Nd5 is.} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 {Various move orders can lead to this position.} Be7 ({This is another possible and common way of responding to} 6... Nxd5 {.}) 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Nf5 {Forcing Black to give us the bishop pair.} Bxf5 9. exf5 O-O 10. O-O {There are some games in this position, and Black was never able to find the right way to equalize.} Ne5 {This is the strongest move in this position, with the idea to take the center with ... c6 and ... d5 at some point.} 11. Nxf6+ {I think the main reason why Black would avoid playing ... Ne5 is to not allow White to get the bishop pair advantage, but I believe this move is better and far more dangerous.} Bxf6 12. f4 Nd7 13. g4 {The idea is very straightforward: we want to push g5 and start the attack.} h6 {By far the most logical move, simply stopping g5 , and h4 is not an option for the moment.} 14. a4 {I like this move a lot, the idea is very simple: we want to bring our a1 -rook to g3 and create a deadly attack!} c6 15. Be2 {It is important to remember that the bishop needs to go to e2 in order not to prevent the rook maneuver.} d5 16. Ra3 Nc5 {A very logical move since the knight on e4 would be very active; meanwhile, it also stops g4 - g5 .} 17. Kh1 {Just a prophylactic move, avoiding all the unnecessary checks, and preparing Rg3 or Rh3 .} Ne4 18. Rh3 {This is a very strong move! Black's ability to equalize is already debatable, as Bd3 and g5 would result in a mating attack since the queen would join the attack after ... hxg5 .} *

