1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} d6 {This is the most common move in the position. It is very natural to make a solid move after you face such a new move like 4.Nd5 is.} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 {Various move orders can lead to this position.} Be7 ({This is another possible and common way of responding to} 6... Nxd5 {.}) 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Nf5 {Forcing Black to give us the bishop pair.} Bxf5 9. exf5 O-O 10. O-O {There are some games in this position, and Black was never able to find the right way to equalize.} Nxd5 {Our knight on d5 is always annoying for Black, so it’s completely understandable why ... Nxd5 is played in so many games since Black just wants to get rid of that active piece.} 11. Qxd5 Qd7 12. c3 {This is a very classy move, it stops the knight from jumping in the future, and it also creates a square for our bishop on c2 ; for instance, after ... a6 , we can play Ba4 and then later on Bc2 .} Rfe8 13. f4 {A very strong move. In the future, the idea is to push g4 - g5 to take all the space and create an attack; later on, Bd2 followed by Rae1 will also be very helpful.} *

