1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Nxe4 5. d4 {I recommend another pawn sacrifice, with the main idea being to open up the position with tempo and to try to create dynamic and active play.} d6 ({This position can arise from a different move order as well:} 5... d6 {d4 Nxe4 , so it's important to know exactly what White is supposed to do here.}) 6. Bb5 ({There are three main ideas after Bb5 . One is} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Nxe5 {, another is attacking the black knight with Qe2 and capturing on e5 after that, and the last idea is simply going for the short castle and attacking the knight on e4 with the rook.}) 6... Nf6 {This is possibly the best and easiest way for Black to equalize in this line.} ({After} 6... exd4 7. Qe2 f5 8. Bg5 Qd7 9. O-O-O {, White is completely winning, as Rxd4 , or Nxd4 followed by f3 are unstoppable. Black's pieces are stuck and it is impossible to get rid of the pins.}) 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qe2 O-O 12. O-O-O {All the moves are quite forced so far, and we get to this position where the objective evaluation is equal, but I believe it is much easier to play with White. We have to try to get the pawn back, and in almost all scenarios, our pawn structure will be better than Black's.} Re8 13. Rhe1 e4 ({After} 13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nxe5 Qf5 16. Qe3 {, a curious draw by perpetual can emerge.} f6 17. g4 Qg5 18. f4 Qh4 19. Ng6 Rxe3 20. Rxe3 Qf2 21. Rd8+ Kh7 22. Nf8+ Kg8 23. Ng6+ {.}) 14. Qc4 {Black is unable to save the pawn advantage, and here White is a little bit better since on the next move, in most cases, we will capture on f6 followed by Rxe4 .} *

