1. e4 e5 ({Over the last few decades, it has been very well known that} 1... e5 {is the best and most solid response to 1.e4 . Nowadays, it's impossible to find any advantage against e5 , and that's because it simply doesn't exist.  It is well known that the Berlin endgames and Ruy Lopez positions are equal, but in this course, I am excited to announce that I will cover something extremely new and interesting, which will shock and surprise our opponents, who will find it difficult to deal with against someone who is well prepared.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {With this move, we are going to the Four Knights opening, which is usually known for its drawish tendency, but our next step is going to change the opening dynamic completely.} 4. Nd5 {The move is a truly unusual one, and I am sure many of you are seeing it for the first time. First of all, it is important to note that this move isn't making a huge difference when it comes to the evaluation, so the position remains equal, but Black needs to make careful moves.  This is a very interesting idea and very fresh. I played it in two Armageddon games, which shows that I do trust this opening even in high-level games.} Nxe4 5. d4 {I recommend another pawn sacrifice, with the main idea of opening up the position with tempo and trying to create dynamic and active play.} d6 ({This position can arise from a different move order as well:} 5... d6 {d4 Nxe4 , so it's important to know exactly what White is supposed to do here.}) 6. Bb5 ({There are three main ideas after Bb5 . One is} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Nxe5 {, another is attacking the black knight with Qe2 and capturing on e5 after that, and the last idea is simply going for the short castle and attacking the knight on e4 with the rook.}) 6... Bd7 {Probably the most logical move in the position. Stopping the pin and developing the kingside as soon as possible is the plan.} ({After} 6... exd4 7. Qe2 f5 8. Bg5 Qd7 9. O-O-O {, White is completely winning, as Rxd4 or Nd4 followed by f3 are unstoppable. Black's pieces are stuck and it is impossible to get rid of the pins.}) 7. O-O Nxd4 (7... Nxd4 {appears to be a natural move that seems like a blunder, but in reality, it isn't.}) 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nxd4 ({exd4 well, clearly, this is the most natural move, which is easily losing:} 9. Re1 f5 {f3 .}) 9... c6 {A very strong intermezzo, White's knight on d5 lacks a good retreat. If it moves to c3 , Black will capture on c3 and then take on d4 . If Ne3 is played, Black will simply capture on d4 , and Re1 is no longer an option.} 10. Nf4 {A very strange-looking move, but keeping the Re1 option alive.} Nf6 11. Nh5 Nxh5 12. Qxh5 exd4 13. Re1+ Kd8 ({The only move since after} 13... Be7 14. Bg5 {, White is winning.}) 14. Qh4+ Kc7 15. Qxd4 {White has compensation for the invested material, as Black's king isn't safe and their kingside is dormant too. We can start building an attack with b4 , a4 , and the bishop might land on e3 .} *

