only and strongest move, with the idea to stop Bb5 . This is a very deep move, and one must be a very strong player to find it.} (10... Be6 {is the most natural reaction, which leads to a losing position.} 11. Bb5 {and on the next move, White will capture the d4 -pawn with the knight, when Black will be unable to castle on any side of the board, and that would lead to a disaster.}) 11. Nh4 {This is a very nice move; the idea is to play f4 and also to remain open to the idea of Bf5 .} Be6 12. f4 {Our ideas are simple: we should do everything to stop ... O-O-O ; right now, ... Qd7 is not an option because of f5 and the bishop is trapped, and in case of other moves, either Rhe1 or Rde1 is always very logical and helpful to play.} Nb4 {A natural move, attacking both the a2 -pawn and the d3 -bishop, but I think practically it is going to lead to a disaster.} 13. f5 Bd7 {The only move.} 14. Rde1 {Threatening Bg7 .} Rg8 {Another only move by Black; it was simply the only way to stop Bg7 .} 15. Bd2 {A very strong move, forcing Black to capture on d3 .} Nxd3+ 16. cxd3 {White poses a significant threat with Bb4 , making the defense of the e7 -bishop impossible.} c5 {This is by far the most natural move, as it stops Bb4 , but it still doesn't save Black.} (16... a5 {is a much better option than c5 since it stops Bb4 and also does not allow Ba5 . After} 17. Qh5 {, White's attack is extremely dangerous: h7 is hanging Re2 - Re1 is coming, and being Black is extremely hard in this position.}) 17. Ba5 {White is winning the queen, as Black's queen is stuck − moving it allows White to capture on e7 with checkmate. If Black plays ... b6 , White will capture on b6 and take the queen on the next move.} *

