n White can still put pressure on the kingside with Ng5 or Bg5 .}) 8. Re1 Ne6 {This is a solid move, and it does seem like Black is just up two pawns for no compensation, but not only is White not worse here, but White is strongly fighting for an advantage.} 9. Bd2 {A very strong move. We have multiple ideas here: one is the b4 - b5 push, making sure that the c6 -knight does not have a good square to go to. Another idea is to push c2 - c3 and try to take the d4 -pawn, and after the trade, we would have powerful bishops on c3 and d3 looking at the black king.} O-O 10. c3 d6 {Some people may be able to feel the danger after ... dxc3 , so for that reason, they will try not to be greedy in this case.} 11. cxd4 Re8 {A reasonable move, trying to be able to take on d4 , protecting the bishop on e7 , and trying to go to ... Nf8 or ... Bf8 .} 12. Re4 {Protecting the pawn and preparing to double the rooks with Qb3 or Qc2 and Rae1 .} Nf8 13. Qb3 Be6 ({After} 13... Bf5 14. Rxe7 {, White has two bishops against a rook and a pawn with a completely winning position thanks to the bishop pair.}) 14. Bc4 {A pawn is hanging on b7 , Rae1 is coming next, and Black should watch out for our Nxe7 and d5 ideas, while h4 and Ng5 are also hanging in the air. Even though Black is a pawn up, White has a dominating position, and I believe it is extremely hard for Black not to make a crucial blunder in these types of situations when the space is lacking.} *

