n White can still put pressure on the kingside with Ng5 or Bg5 .}) 8. Re1 Ne6 {This is a solid move, and it does seem like Black is just up two pawns for no compensation, but not only is White not worse here, but White is strongly fighting for an advantage.} 9. Bd2 {A very strong move. We have multiple ideas here: one is the b4 - b5 push, making sure that the c6 -knight does not have a good square to go to. Another idea is to push c2 - c3 and try to take the d4 -pawn, and after the trade, we would have powerful bishops on c3 and d3 looking at the black king.} O-O 10. c3 dxc3 11. Bxc3 d6 12. Bc2 {This is a very strange situation. White is down two pawns and nothing special is happening yet, but White is almost winning. The attack is about to be very powerful, and the Bc2 idea is very obvious: White wants to go Qd3 and force Black to go ... g6 , which would open up the whole diagonal for our bishop on c3 .} Re8 {This is the only move that doesn't lose directly. The idea is to play ... Nf8 after Qd3 , which also opens up the c8 -bishop and gives Black some space.} 13. Re3 {Another strong idea. Right now our threat is to go Qd3 with tempo and bring the a1 -rook into the game with Rae1 .} Nf8 {Black does not have much of a choice other than trying to bring the bishop to e6 to keep the game going.} 14. Nd4 {We have many strong ideas in this position, one being Nb5 , which is a very strong idea to keep in mind; Rg3 is always a good idea, and Nf5 is also a winning move right now. Even though Black would be able to capture our knight with the bishop, there is simply no logical move left for Black after that.} *

