, and Rhe1 is the way to finish development.} d5 14. Qh4 h6 15. Kb1 {Here, Kb1 has a very deep purpose. The idea is to go Rhe1 on the next move, force Black to move the queen to the only square available, which is d6 , and then we would sacrifice the bishop on h6 with a deadly attack. If the king were on c1 in this situation, ... Qf4 + would exchange queens and lead to a winning position for Black.} f5 {I believe that this is a tough move to find and the only way to equalize for Black, but I believe that practically, it is still better for White.} 16. Rhe1 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Rxf6 18. b4 {Actually, according to the computer, White is still the one who's pressing, so even though White is a pawn down, it is still a safe situation. The idea of b4 is to stop the ... c5 and ... d4 idea, and also prepare Bd2 followed by Re5 .} *

