1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Bd7 (3... Bd7 {is mostly known as the solid approach that avoids a huge amount of theory.}) (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O ({Castling is not the main move, the other option is} 5. c4 {, aiming to get the Maroczy structure. The idea here is extremely simple: we plan to put the rook on e1 and push c3 followed by d4 .}) 5... Nf6 (5... Nc6 6. Re1 Nf6 7. c3 {transposes to the text. We go for this move order just not to allow c3} d5 {.}) 6. Re1 Nc6 7. c3 e6 {The only way for Black to keep the fight for the center, with the idea to meet d4 with ... d5 in the future.} 8. d4 cxd4 {Allowing the d4 - d5 push is not an option.} 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ng8 {This is more of a passive approach, with the idea to bring the knight to f5 via e7 .} 11. Nc3 Nge7 (11... Bb4 {is a pin that can be met in myriad ways. Since often the threat is stronger than the execution,} 12. h4 {can already scare Black with an imminent kingside attack.} Bxc3 13. bxc3 {is not something to worry about since the pawn on c3 can easily be defended by Re3 , which will also be useful in attack.  Speaking about Re3 , this can be played immediately, when we can take with the rook on c3 if needed, or Bd2 is also possible, all with a better position for White.}) 12. Ne2 {A very classy move, with the idea to bring the knight to the kingside and prepare against ... Nf5 .} Nf5 (12... Ng6 13. h4 {, after this move, it is obvious that the knight does not belong on g6 , and the only way to stop the h4 - h5 push is by playing ... h7 - h5 ; after that, the pawn on h5 as well as the g5 -square would stay weak for the rest of the game.}) 13. g4 {This move might seem to weaken our king, but it is the exact opposite. We force Black to go back with their pieces, and the upcoming moves from White will stop Black from castling.} Nfe7 14. Nf4 {The knight goes to h5 and stops Black's development; g7 will be hanging and the bishop won't be able to move.} Ng6 15. Nh5 {Black's position is passive, as it is simply impossible to finish development without any major losses. The knight on h5 is an absolute monster, it stops all the counterplay ideas such as ... h5 and ... f6 and attacks the g7 -pawn at the same time. All that White has to do here is to finish development.} *

