1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Bd7 (3... Bd7 {is mostly known as the solid approach that avoids a huge amount of theory.}) (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O ({Castling is not the main move, the other option is} 5. c4 {, aiming to get the Maroczy structure. The idea here is extremely simple: we plan to put the rook on e1 and push c3 followed by d4 .}) 5... Nf6 (5... Nc6 6. Re1 Nf6 7. c3 {transposes to the text. We go for this move order just not to allow c3} d5 {.}) 6. Re1 Nc6 7. c3 e6 {The only way for Black to keep the fight for the center, with the idea to meet d4 with ... d5 in the future.} 8. d4 cxd4 {Allowing the d4 - d5 push is not an option.} 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. a3 {This is a very deep move. So far, all the moves that we have made are extremely natural, but this move is special. The idea is to prepare Nbd2 , trade the knights, and prevent ... Bb4 , which would lead to a bishop trade.} ({To illustrate that, after} 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Bb4 {, a lot of pieces get exchanged, reducing the potential of our position.}) 11... Be7 12. Nbd2 {We follow the plan to trade the knights.} Nxd2 13. Bxd2 O-O 14. Rc1 {Developing the piece, but the idea is not to fight for the c-file. White does not need to fight for the c-file ever. The idea is to bring the rook to c3 , then d3 , and attack the kingside.} Rac8 15. Rc3 {Bringing the rook to d3 to protect the d4 -pawn and start an attack with Ng5 .} f6 {The main idea of ... f6 is to stop the attack and get rid of the e5 -pawn, but it also creates a weakness on e6 .} 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Rd3 {The idea is to bring the bishop to c3 , and later on put pressure on the e6 -pawn with Re3 and Qe2 .} *

