o fight for the c-file. White does not need to fight for the c-file ever. The idea is to bring the rook to c3 , then d3 , and attack the kingside.} Rfc8 {This is the most common approach. I personally think that, as White, we should be more worried about ... Rac8 , which would keep the option open of Black breaking with ... f6 .} 15. Rc3 {Rc3 appears to be a bid for control of the c-file, but our real objective lies elsewhere.} b5 {A logical approach, trying to create play on the queenside.} 16. Rd3 {White is now revealing exactly what we are trying to achieve. The rook on d3 is protecting the d4 -pawn, and now Ng5 is an idea; in case of ... h6 , we go back to h3 and bring the queen to g4 or h5 , and later on, the rook on d3 can join the attack as well.} b4 17. Ng5 {White is aiming to take on h7 , with the idea of Qh5 + and Rh3 with a mating attack.} h6 ({Black can also play} 17... Bxg5 18. Bxg5 bxa3 19. bxa3 Ne7 {, but here} 20. Qh5 {followed by Rh3 gives White good attacking chances.}) 18. Nh3 {We play Qg4 next, with ideas like Bxh6 , Nf4 - h5 , and Rg3 .} *

