1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Bd7 (3... Bd7 {is mostly known as the solid approach that avoids a huge amount of theory.}) (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 ({This is not the main move in this position, but it is quite as popular as} 4... Qxd7 {.}) 5. O-O Ngf6 6. d3 {This is not the main move in this position. In this case, our plan is to play c4 , bring the knight to c3 , and later on, try to push on the kingside.} g6 7. Nc3 {Change of plans; with the bishop on g7 , we do not want to play c4 and keep the pawn on d3 . Instead, we are taking a very fresh approach, which I believe is very easy to play for White.} Bg7 8. a4 {This is a prophylactic move, with the idea to stop the ... Rb8 and ... b5 counterplay in the future.} O-O 9. Ng5 {This move may seem very strange, but it is a typical idea. White is preparing the f4 - f5 push, and in the future, White's queen can join the attack from e1 to h4 .} h6 10. Nh3 {The knight is on the edge of the board, but here our focus is on Black's kingside. After f4 - f5 , the knight can join the attack from f4 .} a6 11. f4 Rb8 {Black is following the plan of pushing ... b5 .} 12. a5 {It is important to include this move, as it stops ... b5 , and if Black would ever push ... b5 , the a6 -pawn would be a weakness after the trade. The ideas here are quite simple: we will bring our king to h1 , which is a safe square, push f5 , and bring the queen to h4 via e1 .} *

