1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Bd7 (3... Bd7 {is mostly known as the solid approach that avoids a huge amount of theory.}) (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 ({This is not the main move in this position, but it is quite as popular as} 4... Qxd7 {.}) 5. O-O Ngf6 6. d3 {This is not the main move in this position. In this case, our plan is to play c4 , bring the knight to c3 , and later on, try to push on the kingside.} e6 7. c4 {The purpose of this move is to develop the knight to c3 and to restrict Black's play on the queenside while simultaneously maintaining control of the center.} Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {Black made all the logical decisions, finishing development. Right now Black would probably try to create play on the queenside with ... a6 , ... Rb8 , and ... b5 .} 9. Ne1 {A very strong idea, planning to push f4 and g4 to create an attack on the kingside.} a6 10. f4 Rb8 11. a4 {This was not the best way for Black to play, and after a4 , Black is lacking ideas. White is going to push g4 - g5 and start the attack with Qh5 and Rf3 - h3 .} *

