1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Nd7 {This is the main move in this position; it is very ambitious and leads to heavily theoretical lines.} (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. O-O Ngf6 {This natural move is an inaccuracy, as it allows White to get the f1 -square for the bishop and safely take control of the center.} 5. Re1 a6 6. Bf1 {Now White's idea is very easy; all that we need to do is to push c3 , d4 , and take control over the center.} b6 {This is a very smart move, with the idea to go ... Bb7 and attack the e4 -pawn while stopping the c3 and d4 push for a moment.} 7. c3 Bb7 8. d3 {At first glance, this move may seem passive, but the idea is still forging ahead: we'll play Nbd2 , protecting e4 , and then push d4 .} e6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. d4 O-O 11. Bd3 {It is important to use the center wisely − Bd3 helps to protect the e4 -pawn and opens up the f1 -square for the knight.} *

