he main line.}) 14. Bg5 {Black is forced to find an only move, which is not easy for any chess player.} (14. Nxd5 {doesn't work in view of} b5 15. Qb3 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Bd6 17. Bg5 {( Re1 Bxh2+ followed by ... Qh4 is hopeless for White.)} Qb8 {and Black is on the good side of the complications.}) (14. Nxg6 hxg6 {and now} 15. Nxd5 {can be met similarly with} b5 {(more human than the mysterious Rh5} 16. Nf4 {Rb5 , which is the engine's suggestion) Qb3} Bd6 17. g3 O-O {, when White struggles given the weaker structure.}) 14... b5 ({This strong intermezzo is the only way for Black to keep the game going and not lose immediately.} 14... Qc8 {is losing because after} 15. Rac1 {, either Nb5 or Nd5 is impossible to stop.}) (14... f6 {doesn't work either since after} 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Rxe6+ Kf7 17. Qb3 {, all the tactics see White on top.}) 15. Nxb5 axb5 16. Qxb5 Rb8 17. Qa4 {It is important to keep the c6 -square for the knight.} Ra8 18. Qc6 {Only now Qc6 since here the a8 -rook is hanging.} Be7 ({After} 18... Rc8 19. Bxd8 Rxc6 20. Nxc6 {, White is winning.}) 19. Nxd7 {Nb6 is the threat, and ... Rc8 is the only move.} Rc8 20. Bxe7 Kxe7 ({After} 20... Rxc6 21. Bxd8 Kxd7 {( Kxd8 Ne5 Rc2} 22. b4 {is much better for White), it is important to play Ba5± to prevent any counterplay related to ... Rc2 , as now we would have Bc3 available.}) 21. Ne5 {A beautiful move, which stops ... Rxc6 and keeps the material advantage.} *

