1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Nd7 {This is the main move in this position; it is very ambitious and leads to heavily theoretical lines.} (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. O-O a6 5. Bxd7+ ({The main move here is} 5. Bd3 {, but we are looking for a different type of game, where we give away the bishop pair for activity.}) 5... Bxd7 6. c3 {The idea, once again, is very obvious. White wants to take the center with d2 - d4 .} Nf6 ({Other moves, such as} 6... e6 {or g6 , won't stop our} 7. d4 {expansion plans.}) 7. Re1 Bc6 {A strong move, attacking the e4 -pawn and stopping d4 .} 8. d4 {Yet, we sacrifice our pawn. This is the main idea of our opening line − White is sacrificing a pawn in return for activity.} cxd4 {This move has occurred many times, but to be honest, I do not think that this is necessary, it just gives White the c3 -square for the knight.} 9. cxd4 Bxe4 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {Now b7 is hanging, and if Black defends the b7 -pawn, Bg5 is the idea.} d5 (11... e6 12. Qxb7 Qc8 {, not allowing White to give a check on c6 .} 13. Qf3 Be7 14. d5 e5 15. b3 {, a very strong idea.} O-O 16. Nd1 {− the plan was to bring the knight to e3 , aiming to jump to f5 or c4 while keeping the option to play Ba3 or Bg5 later to further enhance the position.}) 12. Bg5 e6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxd5 {Using the pin to win back material, and b7 is hanging as well.} Qe7 ({The only move to protect the b7 -pawn and try to stay in the game. Instead,} 14... Rb8 {is well met by} 15. Ne4 Qg6 16. Qc4 Be7 17. Qc7 Rd8 18. Qxb7 {, when White is on the verge of winning.}) 15. Qa5 {White's position is completely winning. Black is far away from finishing development, and right now the threat is Nd5 - c7 . Most likely, Black will cover it up with some move, and then White is going to continue with Rad1 and d5 , opening up the center as soon as possible since the king is in the center.} *

