1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Nd7 {This is the main move in this position; it is very ambitious and leads to heavily theoretical lines.} (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. O-O a6 5. Bxd7+ ({The main move here is} 5. Bd3 {, but we are looking for a different type of game, where we give away the bishop pair for activity.}) 5... Bxd7 6. c3 {The idea, once again, is very obvious. White wants to take the center with d2 - d4 .} Nf6 ({Other moves, such as} 6... e6 {or g6 , won't stop our} 7. d4 {expansion plans.}) 7. Re1 Bc6 {A strong move, attacking the e4 -pawn and stopping d4 .} 8. d4 {Yet, we sacrifice our pawn. This is the main idea of our opening line − White is sacrificing a pawn in return for activity.} Bxe4 {By far the most natural move, not allowing White to develop the knight to c3 .} 9. Bg5 {The idea is to take on f6 and ruin Black's kingside, when the e4 -bishop would be hanging as well.} d5 {Not an ambitious move at all since it allows White to take the pawn back and create a strong pawn chain on the queenside.} 10. dxc5 e6 11. b4 Be7 12. Nbd2 {No matter what Black decides to do, castling or keeping the bishop pair by moving the bishop back, our idea is the same. White is going to push a4 - a5 , taking all the space on the queenside, and later on, trying to open up one file to use the powerful a5 - b4 - c5 pawn chain.} *

