1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... d6 ({In the Sicilian,} 2... d6 {represents an attempt to play the Najdorf, among other lines.}) 3. Bb5+ {I like this move for blitz games. This avoids the well-known Najdorf, and with my suggestions, we are going to get not-so-known positions where it is easier to be White.} Nd7 {This is the main move in this position; it is very ambitious and leads to heavily theoretical lines.} (3... Nc6 {instead would transpose to the Rossolimo Variation.}) 4. O-O a6 5. Bxd7+ ({The main move here is} 5. Bd3 {, but we are looking for a different type of game, where we give away the bishop pair for activity.}) 5... Bxd7 6. c3 {The idea, once again, is very obvious. White wants to take the center with d2 - d4 .} Nf6 ({Other moves, such as} 6... e6 {or g6 , won't stop our} 7. d4 {expansion plans.}) 7. Re1 Bc6 {A strong move, attacking the e4 -pawn and stopping d4 .} 8. d4 {Yet, we sacrifice our pawn. This is the main idea of our opening line − White is sacrificing a pawn in return for activity.} Bxe4 {By far the most natural move, not allowing White to develop the knight to c3 .} 9. Bg5 {The idea is to take on f6 and ruin Black's kingside, when the e4 -bishop would be hanging as well.} Bd5 {The most common move in this position, which allows us to sacrifice another pawn.} 10. c4 {A very strong pawn sacrifice, with the idea to bring the knight to c3 .} Bxf3 {I think this is a more solid approach since White would have a huge development advantage if the pawn sacrifice was accepted.} 11. Qxf3 cxd4 12. Qxb7 {Right now, Bxf6 with the idea of Qc6 + is the threat.} Qc8 {The queen trade is good for Black.} 13. Qf3 {The incoming f6 -pawn would be hanging (after Bxf6 ) , so Black needs to move the knight away.} Nd7 (13... e5 {is the most stubborn defense, but Black has to play a series of only moves to keep the balance and not end up worse or even lost. After} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 {,} 15. c5 $1 {is a very tricky question to ask Black. Following} Bg7 ({Both} 15... Rg8 16. Nd2 {and} dxc5 17. Qxf6 {are in White's favor.}) 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Ne4 Kh8 ({Just to illustrate the dangers,} 17... dxc5 {is losing again:} 18. Nd6 Qd7 19. Nf5 Kh8 20. Re4 {, with a deadly attack.}) 18. Nxd6 Qxc5 19. Nf5 {, the engine manages to equalize with very precise moves. However, it feels easier to play with White since the Re4 - h4 plan is clear-cut; just make sure to create luft for your king before starting an assault, to avoid getting mated in case Black doubles on the c-file.}) 14. Qe4 {It is important to get the pawn back as soon as possible, and the only way of doing that is with Qe4 , attacking the e7 and d4 -pawns at the same time.} e6 15. Qxd4 {The material is equal, and for now, Black still does have development issues; the bishop on f8 is unable to move since the g7 -pawn would be hanging.} Qc5 {Quite a logical move. Black is behind in development, so the queen trade is definitely the best that Black can hope for.} 16. Qh4 {Again, not allowing Black to play ... Be7 , and keeping the king in the center.} h6 {A very logical move; the idea is to kick the bishop away from this diagonal, so Black could finally go ... Be7 and ... O-O .} 17. Rxe6+ {Surprise! It is very easy to blunder this move, which wins the game immediately.} fxe6 18. Qh5+ {And mate is coming next.} *

