e was accepted.} 11. Qxf3 cxd4 12. Qxb7 {Right now, Bxf6 with the idea of Qc6 + is the threat.} Qc8 {The queen trade is good for Black.} 13. Qf3 {The incoming f6 -pawn would be hanging (after Bxf6 ) , so Black needs to move the knight away.} Nd7 (13... e5 {is the most stubborn defense, but Black has to play a series of only moves to keep the balance and not end up worse or even lost. After} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 {,} 15. c5 $1 {is a very tricky question to ask Black. Following} Bg7 ({Both} 15... Rg8 16. Nd2 {and} dxc5 17. Qxf6 {are in White's favor.}) 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Ne4 Kh8 ({Just to illustrate the dangers,} 17... dxc5 {is losing again:} 18. Nd6 Qd7 19. Nf5 Kh8 20. Re4 {, with a deadly attack.}) 18. Nxd6 Qxc5 19. Nf5 {, the engine manages to equalize with very precise moves. However, it feels easier to play with White since the Re4 - h4 plan is clear-cut; just make sure to create luft for your king before starting an assault, to avoid getting mated in case Black doubles on the c-file.}) 14. Qe4 {It is important to get the pawn back as soon as possible, and the only way of doing that is with Qe4 , attacking the e7 and d4 -pawns at the same time.} e6 15. Qxd4 {The material is equal, and for now, Black still does have development issues; the bishop on f8 is unable to move since the g7 -pawn would be hanging.} Qc5 {Quite a logical move. Black is behind in development, so the queen trade is definitely the best that Black can hope for.} 16. Qh4 {Again, not allowing Black to play ... Be7 , and keeping the king in the center.} Rc8 {This is the best move, but it does not equalize the position, as Black continues to have development issues.} 17. Nd2 {Rad1 with the idea of playing Ne4 is coming next, and again, Black is unable to play ... h6 because of Rxe6 +. Without ... h6 , it is very hard to say how Black is going to finish development.} *

