1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... g6 {This move can lead to many different opening structures, such as Maroczy and Dragon.} 3. Bc4 ({This is a fresh and simple move, unlike the familiar} 3. d4 {. The main idea is c3 , and the bishop on c4 stops the ... d7 - d5 break, which challenges the center after c3 .}) 3... Bg7 4. c3 {The point of c3 is to push d4 and build a strong center.} d6 {The move is logical, but it still gives White the center. Also, Black has to pay attention to Bxf7 + tricks in case they plan an early ... Bg4 .} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 ({It is important not to allow the Nxe4 Nxe4} 8. d5 {trick, which didn't work earlier, as} Nxe4 $2 {would have been met by} 9. Nxe4 {d5 Bb5++- .}) (8. Bb3 {is a solid move, but to prevent ... Bg4 , which could lead to capturing on f3 and an immediate attack on d4 with ... Nc6 , it's better to retreat the bishop to e2 .}) 8... Nc6 9. d5 {Almost always in these structures after ... Nc6 , it is important to push d4 - d5 and gain even more space. Not only does our move come with tempo, but it also prevents any claims in the center that Black might have after ... e5 followed by ... Nd4 , or ... d5 , and then the other knight will land on e4 . We are not willing to offer our opponents such central expansions and counterplay.} Nb8 (9... Ne5 {buries the g7 -bishop after} 10. Nxe5 dxe5 {.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 ({If Black tries to disentangle with} 10... Bg4 {, White has various options to continue. One would be to just ignore that bishop on g4 and play} 11. a4 {, expanding on the queenside as well. Following} Nbd7 12. a5 {, we are not afraid of} Bxf3 {, which only gives us the bishop pair advantage. We can recapture with either our bishop or even with the g-pawn, with a better position. Just in case of Rc8 , pay attention to ... Rxc3 followed by ... Nxe4 sacrificial ideas. It’s best to prevent that from happening with} 13. Ra3 {, when White is again on top.}) ({Another way to play after} 10... Bg4 {is} 11. Be3 Nbd7 12. Nd4 {, where White will enjoy the extra space after the exchange of the light-squared bishops.}) 11. Be3 {White's focus is on the queenside of the board. The main idea is to take control over the c-file with Rc1 , while Nd2 is a solid move to make in the future that protects the e4 -pawn.} *

