1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... g6 {This move can lead to many different opening structures, such as Maroczy and Dragon.} 3. Bc4 ({This is a fresh and simple move, unlike the familiar} 3. d4 {. The main idea is c3 , and the bishop on c4 stops the ... d7 - d5 break, which challenges the center after c3 .}) 3... Bg7 4. c3 {The point of c3 is to push d4 and build a strong center.} d6 {The move is logical, but it still gives White the center. Also, Black has to pay attention to Bxf7 + tricks in case they plan an early ... Bg4 .} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 ({It is important not to allow the Nxe4 Nxe4} 8. d5 {trick, which didn't work earlier, as} Nxe4 $2 {would have been met by} 9. Nxe4 {d5 Bb5++- .}) (8. Bb3 {is a solid move, but to prevent ... Bg4 , which could lead to capturing on f3 and an immediate attack on d4 with ... Nc6 , it's better to retreat the bishop to e2 .}) 8... a6 {A common move in these structures, aiming to prepare the ... b5 push and continue development with ... Bb7 and ... Nbd7 .} 9. O-O b5 10. a3 {Stopping ... b4 .} Bb7 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Re1 ({A solid and sound move; we are aiming to develop all of our pieces harmoniously. The subsequent moves are} 12. Bd2 {and Rc1 .}) *

