1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... g6 {This move can lead to many different opening structures, such as Maroczy and Dragon.} 3. Bc4 ({This is a fresh and simple move, unlike the familiar} 3. d4 {. The main idea is c3 , and the bishop on c4 stops the ... d7 - d5 break, which challenges the center after c3 .}) 3... Bg7 4. c3 {The point of c3 is to push d4 and build a strong center.} Nc6 {This move is a very natural one, but it is not the right reaction, as it simply allows us to get a strong center.} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {An important move to stop e4 - e5 and prepare the knight development to f6 .} 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. d5 {White has full control over the center and the way to proceed is quite simple: just develop the pieces and take the c-file.} *

