1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... g6 {This move can lead to many different opening structures, such as Maroczy and Dragon.} 3. Bc4 ({This is a fresh and simple move, unlike the familiar} 3. d4 {. The main idea is c3 , and the bishop on c4 stops the ... d7 - d5 break, which challenges the center after c3 .}) 3... Bg7 4. c3 {The point of c3 is to push d4 and build a strong center.} e6 {A strong move, preparing to play ... d7 - d5 and not allow White to take full control of the center.} 5. Bb3 {A smart move, with the idea to play d2 - d4 and stop ... d7 - d5 with a tempo.} d5 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 ({If Black plays} 7... c4 {instead, a sample line is} 8. Bc2 Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 Nbc6 11. Nbd2 {, with the idea Re1 followed by Nf1 - e3 to pressure the pawn on d5 . White is slightly better.}) 8. Nxd4 {White blockades the d5 -pawn, controlling the d4 -square; the whole game will focus on these two squares.} Nc6 9. Be3 {It is important not to let Black trade the knights on d4 and force White to take on d4 with the pawn.} Nf6 10. h3 {It is important to stop ... Ng4 .} O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Re1 {White is slightly better, and the idea is to go Na3 - c2 and keep the control of the d4 -square.} *

