1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... a6 {This is a very tricky move. For instance, after d4 , which is by far the most natural move, Black is equalizing very easily.} 3. c3 ({As a result of c3 , 2...a6 is no longer useful in this case. The point of} 3. c3 {is to push 4.d4 and build a strong center, and the only way to stop that center is by playing} d5 {.}) ({If White plays} 3. d4 {instead, after} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {, Black can solve the opening problems with} e5 {, when the b5 -square is no longer available for our knight.}) 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 {White is forcing Black to take on d4 ; otherwise, White would be able to take on c5 , or to go c4 followed by Nc3 .} cxd4 7. cxd4 ({Besides the fact that} 7. Nxd4 {is met by} e5 {, and Bxd4 with} 8. Nc6 {, solving Black's development issues, going for the isolated pawn structure ensures us a dynamic advantage; Nc3 is coming with tempo, and White will develop the typical IQP initiative while Black struggles to coordinate.}) 7... Bg4 8. Nc3 Qd6 (8... Bxf3 $2 {tactics would spell trouble for Black after} 9. Nxd5 Bxd1 10. Nc7+ {.}) 9. Qb3 {White is ahead in development, so we should not be worried about getting doubled pawns on the f-file.} Bxf3 10. gxf3 b5 11. a4 ({White is completely winning. b4 would be met by} 11. Ne4 {, and Black is simply unable to develop the pieces on time.}) *

