1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... a6 {This is a very tricky move. For instance, after d4 , which is by far the most natural move, Black is equalizing very easily.} 3. c3 ({As a result of c3 , 2...a6 is no longer useful in this case. The point of} 3. c3 {is to push 4.d4 and build a strong center, and the only way to stop that center is by playing} d5 {.}) ({If White plays} 3. d4 {instead, after} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {, Black can solve the opening problems with} e5 {, when the b5 -square is no longer available for our knight.}) 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 {White is forcing Black to take on d4 ; otherwise, White would be able to take on c5 , or to go c4 followed by Nc3 .} cxd4 7. cxd4 ({Besides the fact that} 7. Nxd4 {is met by} e5 {, and Bxd4 with} 8. Nc6 {, solving Black's development issues, going for the isolated pawn structure ensures us a dynamic advantage; Nc3 is coming with tempo, and White will develop the typical IQP initiative while Black struggles to coordinate.}) 7... e6 {This is the solid approach. Black's main idea is to play against the isolated pawn on d4 and stop the d4 - d5 break.} 8. Nc3 Qd6 ({After} 8... Bb4 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O {, Black has the same queen issues again, while the bishop would be better off on e7 , to defend the kingside.}) 9. Bd3 {The bishop belongs on d3 , while the knight will go to e4 at some point in the future.} Nc6 10. a3 {The idea of a3 is to stop ... Nb4 , and not let Black control the d5 -square.} Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2 {The ideas here are quite simple: bringing the rooks to e1 and d1 and preparing d4 - d5 or trading the knights on e4 .} ({The classical plan of forming a battery on the b1 - h7 diagonal is too slow. For example, after} 12. Rc1 b5 13. Bb1 Bb7 14. Qd3 Rfd8 {, we are not really threatening anything concrete, while the pressure on the d4 -pawn piles up. Following} 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 f5 {and ... Bf6 , White has to think already about minimizing damages.}) ({In comparison,} 12. Qc2 {prevents} b5 {, which would run into} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 {, when Black has a problem due to the double attack on c6 and h7 .}) *

