1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... e6 {This is probably one of the oldest approaches in chess history, and it leads to many theoretical discussions such as the Paulsen or Taimanov.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {This is an extremely rare idea, and a very strange-looking one as well. The point is to keep the knight on f3 and place the queen on e3 after ... Nc6 .} Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Nc3 {This is the main position of this line. Here Black has many options, and we are going to react to each of these options in different ways.} d5 {This is a very direct approach, but I do not think that it is justified in this case.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 (7... Nb4 8. Bb5+ Bd7 {is met with a strong antidote:} 9. Qe2 $1 {After} Nbxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. O-O {, Black still has to finish development, which isn't so easy given the Ne5 followed by Qb5 + idea, or the potential pin on the d-file with Rd1 . White continues to have a small plus here.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bd3 Bc5 10. Qe2 O-O 11. O-O {Black's c8 -bishop is out of the game, the queen on d5 is not the best either since it will get attacked after Be4 or Rd1 . White is fine with trading the dark-squared bishops since the black bishop is quite a good one, and taking the d-file is something that White should try to achieve. Our next moves are Be4 , attacking the queen, and trading the dark-squared bishops with Be3 .} *

