1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... e6 {This is probably one of the oldest approaches in chess history, and it leads to many theoretical discussions such as the Paulsen or Taimanov.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {This is an extremely rare idea, and a very strange-looking one as well. The point is to keep the knight on f3 and place the queen on e3 after ... Nc6 .} Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Nc3 {This is the main position of this line. Here Black has many options, and we are going to react to each of these options in different ways.} Bb4 {The most natural approach, pinning the knight, with the idea of pushing ... d7 - d5 .} 7. a3 (7. a3 {is more restrictive than Bd2 , which would give Black the extra option of} d6 {. After a3 Bc5} 8. Qg5 h6 9. Qg3 {( Qxg7? Bxf2+ Kxf2} Rg8 {and White has a big problem with the queen.) Nh5} 10. Qh3 {Nf6 , White has to tread carefully given Black's ... e5 idea, which is another upside of 7...d6 .} ({If we follow the same variation but with a3 instead, after Ba5} 10. Bd2 {Bb6 Qg5 h6 Qg3} Nh5 11. Qh3 Nf6 {, White has} 12. e5 {with a nearly winning position.})) 7... Ba5 8. Bd2 {A logical move, stopping the annoying pin, and preparing e4 - e5 .} O-O 9. e5 Ng4 10. Qf4 f5 {This is an active approach. The idea is to go ... Bc7 and capture the e5 -pawn.} 11. h3 Nh6 12. O-O-O {White's e5 -pawn is obstructing Black's development. The idea here for White is to finish development with Bb5 and Rhe1 .} *

