 of the game.} f6 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. O-O-O {It is very safe to castle queenside; the idea for now is to put the queen on the d6 -square and stop the development of Black's pieces.} d5 {The idea here for Black is simple, yet very dangerous. Black is aiming to put the rook on d8 , protecting the d5 -pawn, push ... e5 , and take full control of the center.} 15. Bb5 {The purpose of this move is very simple: it is a developing move; Rhe1 is coming next, and after that Black will never be able to control the center.} a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qe3 {White is controlling the e5 -square, and after Rd2 , Re1 , and Ne5 , White will have a dominating position.} ({After Rb8 , we can calmly defend with} 17. c3 {, not worrying about 'weakening' the light squares since Black has no way to take advantage of that. Next, we can play Rd2 , defending the pawn on f2 and preparing the knight jump to e5 with or without the inclusion of Re1 , depending on the circumstances. White is better.}) *

