1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... e6 {This is probably one of the oldest approaches in chess history, and it leads to many theoretical discussions such as the Paulsen or Taimanov.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {This is an extremely rare idea, and a very strange-looking one as well. The point is to keep the knight on f3 and place the queen on e3 after ... Nc6 .} Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Nc3 {This is the main position of this line. Here Black has many options, and we are going to react to each of these options in different ways.} Bb4 {The most natural approach, pinning the knight, with the idea of pushing ... d7 - d5 .} 7. a3 (7. a3 {is more restrictive than Bd2 , which would give Black the extra option of} d6 {. After a3 Bc5} 8. Qg5 h6 9. Qg3 {( Qxg7? Bxf2+ Kxf2} Rg8 {and White has a big problem with the queen.) Nh5} 10. Qh3 {Nf6 , White has to tread carefully given Black's ... e5 idea, which is another upside of 7...d6 .} ({If we follow the same variation but with a3 instead, after Ba5} 10. Bd2 {Bb6 Qg5 h6 Qg3} Nh5 11. Qh3 Nf6 {, White has} 12. e5 {with a nearly winning position.})) 7... Ba5 8. Bd2 {A logical move, stopping the annoying pin, and preparing e4 - e5 .} d6 {This is a natural way of playing, stopping e4 - e5 and having more peaceful development.} 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Nb5 {An important move to remember − other moves would lead to equality; only with Nb5 , Black is going to face issues: the d6 -pawn is hanging and Black must decide how to deal with it.} Bb6 11. Qe1 {The threat after Qe1 is to go Bg5 to pin the knight and attack the d6 -pawn.} d5 ({After} 11... Ng4 12. Bg5 Bxf2 {( f6} 13. Bh4 {) Qc3} f6 {Bf4} 14. e5 {Bc4+} Kh8 15. h3 {exf4 hxg4 Bxg4 Nxd6 , White is on the good side of the complications.}) 12. Bg5 {Pinning the knight and the queen at the same time. Now e5 is a huge threat, and Black cannot move the queen from d8 since after Bxf6 , White would damage the kingside.} h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Nxg5 {It is important not to hesitate, the piece sacrifice is a must, otherwise, we would lose the e4 -pawn.} hxg5 15. Bxg5 (15. e5 {is impossible to stop, and also f3 is extremely powerful as well, with the idea of Qg3 or Qh4 .}) *

