1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nf6 {Not the most common move, but it is gaining popularity lately, especially in online games.} 3. e5 (3. e5 {is the challenging move. This does seem a bit like an Alekhine Defense, but here Black has some control over the center thanks to the c5 -pawn, but it still is not enough to equalize.}) 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 {Developing the piece and offering a knight trade, after which our pieces would be opened up: the c1 -bishop and the queen on d1 .} ({Retreating the knight would make no sense since after Nc7} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {, White can place the queen almost anywhere and still have a better position; preferable though would be the e4 , f4 , or h4 -square.}) 4... Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 {Protecting the e5 -pawn, and preparing against the ... d7 - d5 break.} e6 7. Nd2 {This move has happened only once before; the idea is to put the knight on e4 or c4 and prevent the ... d7 - d5 break.} d5 (7... d6 8. exd6 {leads to the same thing.}) 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Be3 {Black will find it very hard to stop Ne4 , which attacks the d6 -bishop and c5 -pawn at the same time.} Be7 ({The only logical move to stop Ne4 with a pawn loss. Instead,} 9... Qc7 {is worse since after} 10. Ne4 Be7 11. Qh5 {(stronger than Nxc5 , and also, make sure you don't fall for Bxc5? Bxc5 Nxc5} Qe5 {), White will follow up with O-O-O and develop a strong initiative on the kingside. Given the circumstances, it is hard for Black to finish development and White is much better.}) ({Perhaps it should also be mentioned that} 9... b6 10. Qf3 Bb7 11. O-O-O {is also much better for White.}) 10. Qg4 {A very strong move, attacking the g7 -pawn and preparing O-O-O at the same time.} O-O 11. Bh6 ({More accurate than} 11. O-O-O {, which would unnecessarily hand Black the chance to muddy the waters. After} e5 {followed by ... Kh8 , we would need to find a new setup rather than the strongest one outlined by the text move.}) 11... Bf6 12. O-O-O {Now Ne4 is unstoppable, and Black is in a lot of trouble since their development is incomplete.} *

