1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nf6 {Not the most common move, but it is gaining popularity lately, especially in online games.} 3. e5 (3. e5 {is the challenging move. This does seem a bit like an Alekhine Defense, but here Black has some control over the center thanks to the c5 -pawn, but it still is not enough to equalize.}) 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 {Developing the piece and offering a knight trade, after which our pieces would be opened up: the c1 -bishop and the queen on d1 .} ({Retreating the knight would make no sense since after Nc7} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {, White can place the queen almost anywhere and still have a better position; preferable though would be the e4 , f4 , or h4 -square.}) 4... Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 {Protecting the e5 -pawn, and preparing against the ... d7 - d5 break.} d6 (6... d5 7. exd6 {is the same.}) 7. exd6 exd6 8. Qd2 {By castling on the next move, White is most likely going to win the d6 -pawn cleanly.} ({In case Black holds on to the pawn with d5 O-O-O Be6 , then} 8. Ng5 {will pose new problems. Now Nxe6 , g3 followed by Bg2 or Bh3 , and Rhe1 are ideas that will slowly increase White's positional advantage.}) *

