1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nf6 {Not the most common move, but it is gaining popularity lately, especially in online games.} 3. e5 (3. e5 {is the challenging move. This does seem a bit like an Alekhine Defense, but here Black has some control over the center thanks to the c5 -pawn, but it still is not enough to equalize.}) 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 {Developing the piece and offering a knight trade, after which our pieces would be opened up: the c1 -bishop and the queen on d1 .} ({Retreating the knight would make no sense since after Nc7} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {, White can place the queen almost anywhere and still have a better position; preferable though would be the e4 , f4 , or h4 -square.}) 4... Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 {Protecting the e5 -pawn, and preparing against the ... d7 - d5 break.} Qb6 {This is a little bit more of an advanced-level move. The idea of ... Qb6 is to attack the b2 -pawn and stop White from executing the Qd2 followed by O-O-O idea.} 7. Bd3 {A very strong move! It has already been played by Anish Giri, and the idea of sacrificing two pawns is magnificent. White is ahead in development and in this position, there is no need to worry about the b2 and c3 -pawns.} Qxb2 8. O-O Qxc3 9. Re1 {Currently, White is two pawns down, but we have finished development, and Black is far away from it. The text move protects the e5 -pawn and prepares Ng5 .} ({Just to illustrate how bad Black's position is, White will invest two more pawns in the following sample line: h6} 9. Bd2 Qb2 10. Rb1 Qxa2 11. e6 dxe6 12. Bc3 Qd5 13. Qe2 a6 14. Be4 Qd6 {Red1 Qc7} 15. Bxc6+ Qxc6 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. Ba5 {, when the engine announces mate in 7. It's impossible to beat those computers, but Black had a tough defensive task ahead in the initial position as well.}) 9... e6 10. Ng5 {We follow the plan, White has to use the activity of the pieces as soon as possible and not let Black finish development peacefully.} h6 11. Ne4 Qa5 12. Qg4 {Black is simply unable to finish development, and Nd6 + followed by Qxg7 is impossible to stop.} ({g6 opens up new perspectives after} 12. Bd2 Qc7 13. Bc3 {, when Nd6 + is back on the menu, while Nf6 + is also quite unpleasant for Black to meet.}) *

