1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nf6 {Not the most common move, but it is gaining popularity lately, especially in online games.} 3. e5 (3. e5 {is the challenging move. This does seem a bit like an Alekhine Defense, but here Black has some control over the center thanks to the c5 -pawn, but it still is not enough to equalize.}) 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 {Developing the piece and offering a knight trade, after which our pieces would be opened up: the c1 -bishop and the queen on d1 .} ({Retreating the knight would make no sense since after Nc7} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {, White can place the queen almost anywhere and still have a better position; preferable though would be the e4 , f4 , or h4 -square.}) 4... e6 5. Ne4 ({This is not the main move in this position,} 5. Nxd5 {is. Ne4 creates a simple idea, and the main point is} c4 {with 7.d4 to follow up.}) 5... Nc6 ({A natural move, but not quick enough. Black needs to act fast and make changes in the position to stop} 5... c4 {.}) (5... d6 {would not solve Black's opening problems since after} 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxd6+ Qxd6 10. O-O {, White has a comfortable advantage given the doubled pawns on the c-file.}) 6. c4 Nb6 (6... Nc7 {would face the same treatment:} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. exd6 Na6 10. a3 {, when Black has serious development problems. A sample line is} Nc5 11. b4 Ne4 12. Bd3 Nxd6 13. c5 Nf5 14. Bxf5 exf5 15. O-O O-O 16. b5 Ne7 17. Qxd4 {. White starts regaining the material investment while keeping a very dangerous initiative; Bb2 comes next.}) 7. d4 ({Slightly more precise than} 7. Nd6+ {directly, as after} Bxd6 8. exd6 Qf6 9. d4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 {, White has to pay attention to the check on e5 . If we follow the same variation but with d4 instead, we keep a pair of knights on the board, which benefits White. We would control the e5 -square, while Black has more uncoordinated pieces on the board to worry about.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. exd6 {Even though White is down a pawn, this position is surprisingly winning. The d6 -pawn is extremely strong, it is just paralyzing Black's entire queenside, while the b6 -knight does not have a square, and the c8 -bishop does not have a good future either.} e5 (9... O-O {would be the equivalent of putting one's head in the sand. Black can't ignore White's powerful attack since after} 10. Bd3 {, the Greek gift appears on the horizon too. In addition, the issues in development, which were already present in the position, didn't disappear either.}) 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bd2 O-O 12. c5 {Now d5 is the only square where the knight can be placed, but after Qb3 or Bc4 , Black loses the piece.} *

