1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nf6 {Not the most common move, but it is gaining popularity lately, especially in online games.} 3. e5 (3. e5 {is the challenging move. This does seem a bit like an Alekhine Defense, but here Black has some control over the center thanks to the c5 -pawn, but it still is not enough to equalize.}) 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 {Developing the piece and offering a knight trade, after which our pieces would be opened up: the c1 -bishop and the queen on d1 .} ({Retreating the knight would make no sense since after Nc7} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {, White can place the queen almost anywhere and still have a better position; preferable though would be the e4 , f4 , or h4 -square.}) 4... e6 5. Ne4 ({This is not the main move in this position,} 5. Nxd5 {is. Ne4 creates a simple idea, and the main point is} c4 {with 7.d4 to follow up.}) 5... f5 {This is the main move in this position, with the idea to stop c4 for a moment.} (5... d6 {would not solve Black's opening problems since after} 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxd6+ Qxd6 10. O-O {, White has a comfortable advantage given the doubled pawns on the c-file.}) 6. exf6 ({Here} 6. Nc3 {is the known theory, but I like this approach as well. It is less known, and I believe that practically, it is better to play this.}) 6... Nxf6 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. d4 cxd4 ({After} 8... Nc6 {, White can play} 9. Bg5 Qf7 10. Be2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 {with a better position, or just transpose to the text with Be3 cxd4} Nxd4 {.}) 9. Nxd4 Nc6 (9... Bc5 $2 {is a very natural move, which blunders a piece to} 10. Qh5+ {.}) 10. Be3 {The ideas here are quite simple: White is going to develop with g3 , Bg2 , and O-O .} Be7 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 d5 13. O-O {Black cannot use the 'strong' center since the d5 -pawn is hanging after the ... e6 - e5 pawn push. White's ideas are quite simple: f4 and c3 , making sure that we control the center, and later on bringing the rooks to the game with Re1 , Qd2 , and Rad1 .} *

