1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e5 {Lately, this has gained a lot of popularity; the idea is to bring the bishop to d6 and the knight to e7 .} 4. O-O Bd6 5. d3 {A tricky move, with the idea to keep the c3 -square for the knight. We do not try to make c3 - d4 work. Instead, we are trying to play Nc3 and Bc4 to take control over the d5 -square.} Nf6 6. Bg5 {Pinning the knight; the plan is to play Nc3 - d5 .} a6 {In order to get rid of the pin, Black needs to play ... Be7 , and for that, they need to make sure that they would not allow Bxc6 .} 7. Bc4 Be7 ({Instead,} 7... b5 {would weaken Black's position since after} 8. Bd5 {, we would also get a4 ideas on a silver platter.}) 8. Bxf6 {Eliminating the knight to gain control over the d5 -square.} Bxf6 9. a4 {Stopping ... b5 .} O-O 10. Nc3 d6 11. Nd5 {Our ideas here are quite simple: we should keep control over the d5 -square, play c3 , later on, h3 , and prepare some action on the queenside.} *

