1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e5 {Lately, this has gained a lot of popularity; the idea is to bring the bishop to d6 and the knight to e7 .} 4. O-O Nge7 {The move has been played by Dubov a couple of times. The idea is to protect the c6 -knight and prepare ... g6 followed by ... Bg7 .} 5. c3 {The most logical approach − our plan is to push d4 and take the center.} g6 6. Bxc6 {A very strong and direct move, forcing Black to capture on c6 with the knight.} Nxc6 7. d4 {Opening up the center.} cxd4 8. cxd4 exd4 9. Nxd4 Bg7 {So far, the variation has been quite logical.} 10. Nb5 {White is aiming to put the knight on d6 and stop Black's development.} O-O 11. Nd6 {White has a dominating advantage. Black's pieces are stuck, and by simply developing the knight to c3 and the bishop on f4 White should have a long-lasting advantage.} *

