1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 a6 {This move is actually very common, but it is just a waste of tempo since White is more than happy to capture on c6 .} 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qc7 ({The idea behind} 5... Qc7 {is to push ... e5 and grab the center.}) (5... Bg4 {is a logical move, pinning the knight, but it's not particularly strong.} 6. h3 Bh5 7. d3 {, and now Black can't push ... e7 - e5 because g4 would win the e5 -pawn. To prepare ... e5 , Black plays} Qc7 {. But after} 8. g4 Bg6 {,} 9. Nh4 {is a powerful move, aiming to push f4 - f5 and trap the g6 -bishop. Black's position becomes critical. If} e5 {, then} 10. f4 {gives White a significant advantage, and after Bxf4 following the exchange on f4 , White's position only strengthens.}) 6. a4 {A very strong move, the idea is to push a4 - a5 and later try to attack the c5 -pawn, when Black would not be able to protect it with ... b6 .} a5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 {White gets control over the center. The main idea here is to go Nbd2 followed by Nc4 .} *

