1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 Nf6 {Lately, this move has been played by a lot of top grandmasters. Caruana used this move three times during the Candidates tournament.} 4. e5 {A very direct approach.} Nd5 5. Nc3 Nc7 {Exchanging on c3 is not good for Black since White will capture with the d-pawn, and Black is simply too far away from developing all their pieces properly.} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. h3 {The idea is to stop ... Bg4 and leave the c8 -bishop without good squares.} g6 {The only logical way to develop the f8 -bishop.} 8. O-O Bg7 9. d3 O-O 10. Be3 {Attacking the c5 -pawn and preparing Qd2 followed by Bh6 .} b6 11. Qd2 ({In this position, White is obviously very active, and the pawn structure is very good for White. With the next move,} 11. Bh6 {, White will eliminate Black’s advantage, which is the two bishops.}) *

