1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} a6 5. Bxc6 bxc6 ({The idea of taking with the b-pawn is to keep the d-pawn to help the center. After} 5... dxc6 6. d3 {, the engine recommends the pawn sacrifice} e5 {as a way to try to disentangle and speed up development.} 7. Nxe5 {, thank you very much!}) 6. O-O ({We castle first, as} 6. d4 {directly allows} d5 {, when we no longer have the option of d3 .}) 6... d5 {A common move in these types of structures, but usually it is not very good since the c5 -pawn is left all alone; our plan with White here is to develop the pieces properly and attack the c5 -pawn.} 7. d3 {The idea is very simple: Be3 and Nbd2 , and later on planning to attack on c5 with Nb3 .} Ne7 8. Be3 Ng6 9. Nbd2 ({White is simply better. The next moves are} 9. Qa4 {, attacking the c6 -pawn, and then bringing the knight to b3 , trying to put pressure on the c5 -pawn.}) *

