1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} a6 5. Bxc6 bxc6 ({The idea of taking with the b-pawn is to keep the d-pawn to help the center. After} 5... dxc6 6. d3 {, the engine recommends the pawn sacrifice} e5 {as a way to try to disentangle and speed up development.} 7. Nxe5 {, thank you very much!}) 6. O-O ({We castle first, as} 6. d4 {directly allows} d5 {, when we no longer have the option of d3 .}) 6... Ne7 {This is usually a safe way to develop the knight, as the knight is standing better on g6 .} 7. d4 Ng6 8. g3 {A very classy move; the idea is to push h4 - h5 and leave the g6 -knight with no squares.} cxd4 9. cxd4 Be7 10. h4 h5 {This is a natural move, stopping h5 , but in the long run, it is not so good because Black is not going to be able to castle short peacefully.} 11. Be3 {The knight is better on d2 than on c3 , and for that reason, we develop the bishop first.} d6 ({Black needs to delay castling short so that the h5 -pawn would not be hanging. After} 11... O-O 12. Nh2 {, White wins a pawn.}) 12. Nbd2 {Black must castle at some point, and then with moves like Nh2 or Ng5 , White will be able to take the h5 -pawn; otherwise, White would just put pressure on the c6 -pawn and improve the pieces with Rc1 and Re1 .} *

