1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} a6 5. Bxc6 bxc6 ({The idea of taking with the b-pawn is to keep the d-pawn to help the center. After} 5... dxc6 6. d3 {, the engine recommends the pawn sacrifice} e5 {as a way to try to disentangle and speed up development.} 7. Nxe5 {, thank you very much!}) 6. O-O ({We castle first, as} 6. d4 {directly allows} d5 {, when we no longer have the option of d3 .}) 6... Ne7 {This is usually a safe way to develop the knight, as the knight is standing better on g6 .} 7. d4 Ng6 8. g3 {A very classy move; the idea is to push h4 - h5 and leave the g6 -knight with no squares.} cxd4 9. cxd4 Be7 10. h4 O-O {Funnily enough, this is the best move according to the computers.} 11. h5 Nh8 {Probably for the majority of you, the knight on h8 will look horrible, but actually, it is not so bad. If White plays passively, after ... f6 and ... Nf7 , Black's knight would be in very good shape.} 12. h6 {White must act very quickly and not let Black achieve the desirable setup.} g6 13. e5 {The point of e5 is to fight against the ... f6 and ... Nf7 plan, and also, if it is possible and if Black would not act quickly, we would love to bring the knight to e4 and take control over the d6 and f6 -squares.} f6 {Black must play ... f6 , otherwise, the position would only get worse.} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Nc3 Nf7 16. Ne4 Be7 {Now it may seem that Black is able to equalize. The idea is to push ... d5 and put the bishop on d6 .} 17. d5 {A very important move, and the only move which gives White a winning advantage. After either capture, Qd4 wins the game.} *

