1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} d5 5. d3 {A modern approach; the idea is quite simple: White wants to capture on c6 and play c4 to fix the bad pawn structure.} Bd7 6. exd5 exd5 7. O-O {Quite an interesting idea − the plan is to give Re1 + and at some point play c4 .} Nf6 8. Re1+ Be7 9. Qe2 {Black is unable to castle since White will capture on c6 and then on e7 . Since Black can't really castle, we will need to play very quickly: Bg5 with the idea of Bxf6 is very strong and hard to stop.} *

