1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} d5 5. d3 {A modern approach; the idea is quite simple: White wants to capture on c6 and play c4 to fix the bad pawn structure.} Bd7 6. exd5 exd5 7. O-O Bd6 {The strongest move by far. Black wants to develop the knight on e7 .} 8. c4 {Unique, very strong, and the only move that can fight for an advantage.} d4 {Black does not want to allow White to bring the knight to c3 , but it does not change our plans.} 9. Nbd2 {The knight still goes to e4 .} Nge7 10. Ne4 Qc7 11. Nxd6+ Qxd6 12. Ng5 {The other knight goes to e4 .} Bf5 13. Re1 {White has the bishop pair advantage; objectively, the position is probably equal, but I believe that it is much easier to be White here since the game plan is pretty straightforward. The knight goes to e4 , and later on, we develop the bishop to f4 or g5 .} *

