1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 e6 4. c3 {Not the most common move in this position, but the idea is quite obvious: to push d4 and take the center.} Nge7 {This is the most common move here, which immediately gives White an advantage.} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d5 {Black fights for the center, preventing d5 from White as well.} 7. e5 {The center of the board has already been dominated by White.} Bd7 {This move has been played by the majority of players, with the idea to get rid of the pin and also create the ... Nxe5 threat.} ({Getting rid of the pin with} 7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2 {would only give White additional scope on the queenside in the future.}) 8. Nc3 {Developing the piece and protecting the b5 -bishop.} Nf5 9. O-O Qb6 10. Be3 {We do not need to worry about ... Nxe3 since the f-file would open up. The benefit can be seen in the variation Nxe3 fxe3 Nxe5? because now White can simply play Nxe5 Bxb5 Nxb5 Qxb5 Rxf7 or Nxf7 with a winning position.} Be7 11. Bd3 {This time forcing Black to take on e3 and open up the f-file for us.} Nxe3 ({Once again, after} 11... Nfxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qg4 {, the position is hopeless after White captures on g7 .}) 12. fxe3 O-O 13. Qc2 h6 ({The threat on h7 is pretty serious and Black doesn't have time for} 13... Nb4 {since after} 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Qb1 {, trapping the bishop with} g6 {would only add more fuel to the fire.  Following} 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Qxg6 Qd8 18. Rf2 {, White has already three pawns for the piece and a deadly attack; there is no rush to deliver mate immediately, we can just slowly bring all the pieces into the game. A sample continuation is} Qe8 19. Qh6+ Kg8 20. Ng5 Bxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh7 22. Raf1 {, where Black will succumb soon after, as the king is left alone on the battle field.}) 14. a3 {Our play is very straightforward here, we want to double the rooks on the f-file and create an attack on the kingside.} *

