1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 d6 {The idea of ... d6 is to put the bishop on d7 and play ... a6 .} 4. Bxc6+ {This is an unknown move; again, avoiding the main theory, but keeping it fresh and interesting.} bxc6 5. O-O {Now White has two different ideas: the main one is to push e5 , which is extremely strong and annoying for Black, and another idea is c3 followed by d4 , taking the center.} g6 6. e5 Bg7 7. Re1 {We are trying to eliminate the d6 -pawn and leave Black with the weak c5 and c6 -pawns. The same would happen after the ... d6 - d5 push: the c5 -pawn would be a weakness for the rest of the game.} Nh6 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. d3 {Next, the b1 -knight can go to e4 or c4 , and for the rest of the game, White will try to play on the weaknesses on the c-file.} *

