1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 d6 {The idea of ... d6 is to put the bishop on d7 and play ... a6 .} 4. Bxc6+ {This is an unknown move; again, avoiding the main theory, but keeping it fresh and interesting.} bxc6 5. O-O {Now White has two different ideas: the main one is to push e5 , which is extremely strong and annoying for Black, and another idea is c3 followed by d4 , taking the center.} e5 {The most natural approach, taking the center.} 6. c3 {The idea is to push d4 and eliminate the strong grip Black has in the center.} Nf6 ({After} 6... f5 7. d4 fxe4 8. Ng5 Bf5 9. f3 {, Black has to tread carefully to not be worse.}) 7. Re1 Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Qc7 {This is the most common move in this position. Black is still trying to fight for the center.} (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 {and now that Black's center is gone, White's pieces can 'breathe' and develop freely.}) 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Nbd2 {Black does have the bishop pair, but White has a clear plan of attacking the c6 -pawn.} Be6 13. Qc2 {Keeping the pressure on the c6 -pawn with Rac1 is our plan.} *

