1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 d6 {The idea of ... d6 is to put the bishop on d7 and play ... a6 .} 4. Bxc6+ {This is an unknown move; again, avoiding the main theory, but keeping it fresh and interesting.} bxc6 5. O-O {Now White has two different ideas: the main one is to push e5 , which is extremely strong and annoying for Black, and another idea is c3 followed by d4 , taking the center.} Bg4 {The idea is to develop a piece and pin the knight.} 6. h3 Bh5 7. Re1 {In order to prevent Black from developing the knight, White now wants to push e5 , which will also lead to a weakness after ... exd6 since Black will have to capture with the queen; the c5 and c6 -pawns will remain weak for the rest of the game.} ({In case of} 7. e5 {, after c3 , White’s idea is very simple: we want to push d4 and take control over the center.}) 7... Nf6 8. e5 dxe5 9. Rxe5 {White succeeded in exposing the c-file's weaknesses. Our next move is to bring the rook back to e1 and begin developing with d3 , Nbd2 , and Nc4 .} *

