1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 g6 {This move became extremely popular during the World Championship match between Caruana and Carlsen, and after that, a lot of people started to study the Rossolimo.} 4. c3 {Usually, Black's idea is to go ... Bg7 and ... e5 , and for now, with c3 , we are trying to take the center with d4 .} Nf6 {This is the only move to stop the d4 push and White's control in the center.} ({Following} 4... Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 {, White is already better, and Black has to watch out for e5 as well.}) 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O Bg7 {A logical move, trying to finish development.} 7. d4 cxd4 (7... O-O {does not make a lot of sense. It is just a free pawn for White after} 8. dxc5 {, and Black does not have compensation.}) 8. cxd4 O-O 9. Nc3 {The knight on d5 is extremely strong and that is the reason why we are fine with the trade of knights.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 {Right now, we have a strong pawn chain and to fight against it, Black should try to undermine the e5 -pawn.} d6 11. e6 {Sacrificing the pawn to weaken the kingside and stop Black's development.} fxe6 (11... Bxe6 12. d5 {and there is nothing Black can do about the fork.}) 12. Rb1 {The rook can be useful in the future to join the attack via b4 to h4 .} e5 {The plan is to challenge White's center, make the f8 -rook useful, and open the c8 -bishop − by far the most sensible move.} 13. d5 Na5 ({In case of} 13... Nb8 {, a sample line is} 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. Ne6 Qc8 16. Bd3 Bxe6 17. dxe6 Na6 18. Bxa6 bxa6 19. Qd5 Qxc3 20. Bg5 Rae8 21. Rb7 {, when White keeps some practical chances despite the material deficit.}) 14. Rb4 {The plan is to prevent ... Bg4 , and on b4 , the rook is quite helpful since it can be employed for both the attack and defense.} Bf5 {Completing the bishop's development.} 15. g4 Bd7 16. Ng5 {White now has several options. One is to move the queen to h3 , forcing Black to create a weakness on the kingside. The a5 -knight is out of the game, while the bishop trade would only offer us the e6 -square, and the g7 -bishop is also blocked in.} *

