1. e4 c5 ({To White's 1.e4 , the Sicilian Defense is the most popular response. The opening has a reputation for leading to very sharp positions, yet it also depends on how both sides decide to keep the game going. After} 1... c5 {, we are going to play mostly sidelines where Black has to play very carefully.}) 2. Nf3 ({This is the most logical and sound move here, simply developing the knight. Usually, the idea is to push} 2. d4 {, but in some cases, we are going to make different moves, avoiding main line theory.}) 2... Nc6 {This move has always been very popular; the main idea of this opening is to play the Sveshnikov Defense, but with our third move, we avoid those lines.} 3. Bb5 g6 {This move became extremely popular during the World Championship match between Caruana and Carlsen, and after that, a lot of people started to study the Rossolimo.} 4. c3 {Usually, Black's idea is to go ... Bg7 and ... e5 , and for now, with c3 , we are trying to take the center with d4 .} Nf6 {This is the only move to stop the d4 push and White's control in the center.} ({Following} 4... Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 {, White is already better, and Black has to watch out for e5 as well.}) 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O Bg7 {A logical move, trying to finish development.} 7. d4 Nc7 {A common move in these positions.} 8. Ba4 cxd4 9. cxd4 O-O {This is probably the best approach from Black's side; the idea is to push ... d6 next and create an isolated pawn for White.} 10. Qe2 d6 11. Rd1 {By preparing against the move ... dxe5 , we plan to recapture and then launch an attack on the queen.} Bg4 {Black must create counterplay, as otherwise, White will simply push h2 - h3 and later on develop the knight to c3 and have full control of the center.} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 d5 {This has been played couple of times, but it is giving us an advantage.} 14. Qg4 {A very strong move; the idea is to have f4 in case of ... f7 - f6 , to stop Black's only counterplay.} *

