1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} c5 ({There are two main moves after e5 , and} 3... c5 {is one of them. The objective is to challenge White's center as soon as possible.}) 4. Nf3 ({This is the second most common move in this position. The most played move is} 4. dxc5 {, which leads to a huge amount of theory. With Nf3 , we are able to keep an advantage and I believe it is much easier to play and to remember the ideas.}) 4... cxd4 {This is the most logical response, with the purpose of eliminating the central pawn.} 5. Nxd4 ({Currently, Black has only two logical moves: Nc6 and} 5. e6 {, but if Black makes another move, White will simply continue developing with Bd3 , O-O , bringing the b1 -knight to the f3 -square, and attempting to take full control of the center.}) 5... e6 6. Nd2 {White has an easy time playing against this passive approach.} Ne7 7. N2f3 {This is the best setup for White, protecting the d4 -knight and e5 -pawn at the same time.} Nbc6 8. Bd3 Nxd4 (8... Ng6 9. Nxc6 {would transpose to the 5...Nc6 variation .}) 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O Be7 {Definitely the most logical move.} 12. Qg4 {A very strong move, stopping Black from castling kingside and forcing them to play ... Kf8 .} Kf8 (12... O-O $2 13. Bh6 $1 {and if} g6 {Bh6± .}) 13. c4 {White has more space thanks to the e5 -pawn. Black will never be able to castle, and with Be3 and Rac1 , White could take control over the other side of the board as well.} *

