1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} c5 ({There are two main moves after e5 , and} 3... c5 {is one of them. The objective is to challenge White's center as soon as possible.}) 4. Nf3 ({This is the second most common move in this position. The most played move is} 4. dxc5 {, which leads to a huge amount of theory. With Nf3 , we are able to keep an advantage and I believe it is much easier to play and to remember the ideas.}) 4... cxd4 {This is the most logical response, with the purpose of eliminating the central pawn.} 5. Nxd4 ({Currently, Black has only two logical moves: Nc6 and} 5. e6 {, but if Black makes another move, White will simply continue developing with Bd3 , O-O , bringing the b1 -knight to the f3 -square, and attempting to take full control of the center.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {It seems that Black benefits from this trade since the pawn center improves, but I don't believe it helps Black to fully equalize. We will focus on our strengths, which are the e5 -pawn and the attack on the kingside.} 7. Bd3 {Here, the ideas for White are very simple: White is planning to bring the knight to the f3 -square, castle kingside, and plan an attack.} e6 {This is the only logical approach to development.} 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nd2 {We follow the main idea of putting the knight on f3 and the rook on e1 .} Ng6 {Probably the move that would occur in our games the most... Black is trying to continue developing without revealing any deep ideas.} 10. Nf3 Be7 11. Re1 {We stick to our original idea of bringing the knight to f3 and rook to e1 , preparing the g3 and h4 attack.} O-O 12. g3 f6 {Black is about to face a powerful attack, with h4 and Ng5 , or h5 - h6 . To stop that, Black must create counterplay as soon as possible, and ... f6 or ... f5 is the only way to do that.} 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. h4 {Again, h5 - h6 is one idea, h5 in combination with Bf4 is another idea to take control of the dark squares, while Ng5 is also very powerful. The only way for Black to stop all these ideas is by sacrificing a pawn.} e5 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Rxe5 Bf5 18. Bf4 {Yes, it is an opposite-colored bishops position, but White is playing for a win here. First of all, we are a pawn up, our king is safer, and we have a better pawn structure. Our next ideas are also very simple: Qd2 , Rae1 , controlling the only open file, and to keep improving the position slowly.} *

