1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} c5 ({There are two main moves after e5 , and} 3... c5 {is one of them. The objective is to challenge White's center as soon as possible.}) 4. Nf3 ({This is the second most common move in this position. The most played move is} 4. dxc5 {, which leads to a huge amount of theory. With Nf3 , we are able to keep an advantage and I believe it is much easier to play and to remember the ideas.}) 4... cxd4 {This is the most logical response, with the purpose of eliminating the central pawn.} 5. Nxd4 ({Currently, Black has only two logical moves: Nc6 and} 5. e6 {, but if Black makes another move, White will simply continue developing with Bd3 , O-O , bringing the b1 -knight to the f3 -square, and attempting to take full control of the center.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {It seems that Black benefits from this trade since the pawn center improves, but I don't believe it helps Black to fully equalize. We will focus on our strengths, which are the e5 -pawn and the attack on the kingside.} 7. Bd3 {Here, the ideas for White are very simple: White is planning to bring the knight to the f3 -square, castle kingside, and plan an attack.} e6 {This is the only logical approach to development.} 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nd2 {We follow the main idea of putting the knight on f3 and the rook on e1 .} a5 {This is a very common move in this position, with a very strong idea. As we can see, our bishop on d3 is watching out the h7 -square and will become a very powerful one when Black eventually castles, so for that reason, Black does not mind trading the bad bishop on c8 for the strong bishop on d3 .} 10. Qe2 {The idea is very simple and clear, White should try to stop ... Ba6 .} Ng6 {... Ng6 is a very logical move for Black since they should eventually try to develop their pieces.} 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Re1 O-O {This is the main position. Both sides are already developed, and now it is time to take action. There are several ideas for White, but the main one is going to be focused on g3 followed by h4 - h5 . Playing g3 right now is not very good since it allows ... f6 , so for that reason, we are going to make a useful waiting move.} 13. c3 {A prophylactic move. Black is obviously going to push ... c6 - c5 at some point, and in order to stop ... c5 - c4 , we should prepare for that with c3 .} c5 14. g3 {Now it is time to start our plan with g3 and h4 .} f6 {A high-level player will know right away what is about to take place. Allowing h4 - h5 - h6 or h4 followed by Ng5 is extremely dangerous, but a player of a bit lower level may have a hard time understanding that allowing h4 is deadly.} 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. h4 {We keep attacking; right now there are many threats, so it is important to be on the lookout for Ng5 opportunities, while h5 - h6 is another idea, trying to weaken the kingside; h5 followed by Bf4 is another interesting approach − the main idea here is to control the dark squares.} e5 ({There is only one move that can keep the game alive, but it is very hard to find. Black must realize that after the} 16... h5 {e4 complications, they are able to equalize, and that after} 17. Bxg6 {, the position is still playable despite the fact that they are a pawn down.}) 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Nxe5 {White is a pawn up, and for the moment it is extremely hard for Black to show equality. White is going to develop the bishop to f4 , protecting the e5 -knight, and in case we are pinned, d3 is a great square for the queen to run away to, as the queen would then instantly attack both the d5 and g6 -pawns.} *

