1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} c5 ({There are two main moves after e5 , and} 3... c5 {is one of them. The objective is to challenge White's center as soon as possible.}) 4. Nf3 ({This is the second most common move in this position. The most played move is} 4. dxc5 {, which leads to a huge amount of theory. With Nf3 , we are able to keep an advantage and I believe it is much easier to play and to remember the ideas.}) 4... Bg4 5. Bb5+ {This is not the main move, but it is a very good one, and it puts Black in a tough situation where they have to find many moves in order not to be in a very bad position.} Nc6 6. dxc5 e6 {This is probably the most natural move, especially in faster time controls, but it simply leads to a pawn-down position with no compensation whatsoever.} 7. b4 a5 (7... Nge7 8. Nbd2 a6 9. Ba4) 8. c3 {We are a pawn up, and also ahead in development; the only thing that White has to make sure of is not to lose the b4 or e5 -pawns.} *

