1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} c5 ({There are two main moves after e5 , and} 3... c5 {is one of them. The objective is to challenge White's center as soon as possible.}) 4. Nf3 ({This is the second most common move in this position. The most played move is} 4. dxc5 {, which leads to a huge amount of theory. With Nf3 , we are able to keep an advantage and I believe it is much easier to play and to remember the ideas.}) 4... Bg4 5. Bb5+ {This is not the main move, but it is a very good one, and it puts Black in a tough situation where they have to find many moves in order not to be in a very bad position.} Nc6 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 e6 {This is the best way to play as Black, as ... Qa5 + helps to avoid the c3 and b4 idea.} 8. Bd2 {Using a smart tactical resource to keep the pawn advantage for a few moves.} Qc7 (8... Bxc5 9. Nxd5 {and Black is unable to capture on b5 , because of Nc7 +.}) 9. b4 {Usually in these types of structures, it is better to keep the c5 -pawn and preserve the advantage on the queenside. At first, it may seem that Black is also controlling the center, but having the advantage on the queenside is almost always better than the center that Black has.} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Nxe2 {I like this position, as the ideas are simple. White needs to castle short and start pushing on the queenside with moves like a4 - a5 or c4 .} *

