1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} Bf5 4. Bd3 {This move isn't very well known, as it is not the most common approach in this position, but it is very interesting, and I believe that the ideas are very simple as well. I would absolutely recommend this for any time control, I think this is just a great move with simple play for White.} Bxd3 5. Qxd3 {At the moment, our threat is to push e5 - e6 and create weaknesses and development issues for Black.} e6 (5... Qa5+ {is a natural response, as the idea of trading queens is very well known, but it transposes to the e6 variation after, for example,} 6. c3 Qa6 7. Qd1 e6 8. Ne2 {.}) 6. Ne2 {It is important to know what White should do in this structure since Black has many options. Our first principle is to never trade the queen, and our idea is to place the b1 -knight on f3 with Nd2 - f3 and make the center solid with c3 . Afterwards, White will always pay attention to where the black knight on g8 goes. If it goes to f5 , the g2 - g4 push or the Ne2 - g3 trade may prove critical. Whenever a knight goes to g6 , it is a good idea to play g3 and h4 .} Qa5+ 7. c3 Qa6 {This idea is extremely modern nowadays, as trading queens usually favors Black.} 8. Qd1 {So we keep the queens.} c5 {The only natural continuation in this position. In case of other moves, we still keep our main idea of O-O and transfer the b1 -knight to the f3 -square.} 9. Nd2 {We keep doing the same here as well.} Nc6 10. Nf3 Nge7 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 {This is the main position that occurs after ... Qa5 +. Right now there are two logical moves, but I believe that neither of these options is equalizing.} Ng6 {Bishop to e7 and ... O-O is the main idea, but the knight on g6 will probably struggle to successfully stay put on that square due to our h4 or g3 and h4 ideas.} 13. h4 {This leads to a straightforward position and is very easy to play.} h5 14. Nf4 Nxf4 15. Bxf4 Be7 16. Re1 {I really like this move. The idea is to bring the rook to e3 no matter which side Black castles on and start an attack.} O-O ({Better is} 16... O-O-O {, but after} 17. a3 Kb8 18. b4 {, it is easier to conduct the attack for White than face a long-term assault as Black.}) 17. Re3 {Now Ng5 is extremely strong; h5 is going to hang so Black is going to waste a tempo on playing ... g7 - g6 and after that, Rg3 would create a deadly attack with the idea of sacrificing on e6 . It is important to be prepared to play g2 - g4 after ... g6 , as this is also an option and should be considered.} *

