1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} Bf5 4. Bd3 {This move isn't very well known, as it is not the most common approach in this position, but it is very interesting, and I believe that the ideas are very simple as well. I would absolutely recommend this for any time control, I think this is just a great move with simple play for White.} Bxd3 5. Qxd3 {At the moment, our threat is to push e5 - e6 and create weaknesses and development issues for Black.} e6 (5... Qa5+ {is a natural response, as the idea of trading queens is very well known, but it transposes to the e6 variation after, for example,} 6. c3 Qa6 7. Qd1 e6 8. Ne2 {.}) 6. Ne2 {It is important to know what White should do in this structure since Black has many options. Our first principle is to never trade the queen, and our idea is to place the b1 -knight on f3 with Nd2 - f3 and make the center solid with c3 . Afterwards, White will always pay attention to where the black knight on g8 goes. If it goes to f5 , the g2 - g4 push or the Ne2 - g3 trade may prove critical. Whenever a knight goes to g6 , it is a good idea to play g3 and h4 .} Qa5+ 7. c3 Qa6 {This idea is extremely modern nowadays, as trading queens usually favors Black.} 8. Qd1 {So we keep the queens.} c5 {The only natural continuation in this position. In case of other moves, we still keep our main idea of O-O and transfer the b1 -knight to the f3 -square.} 9. Nd2 {We keep doing the same here as well.} Nc6 10. Nf3 Nge7 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 {This is the main position that occurs after ... Qa5 +. Right now there are two logical moves, but I believe that neither of these options is equalizing.} Nf5 13. g4 {A very important idea to be aware of. It may seem a little bit dangerous to push the king pawn and open our kingside, but actually, this is a very strong positional move.} Nfe7 14. Nf4 {Right now we have won a tempo and activated our knight, and Black is still struggling with development.} Ng6 15. Nh5 {This is the main idea of the g2 - g4 push. White's knight on h5 is amazing! First of all, it stops all the attacking ideas from Black's perspective, attacks the g7 -pawn, and again delays Black's development. It is very likely that at some point Black is going to castle long, but then the a3 and b4 idea is very strong, and it is hard to say how Black would ever be able to equalize the game with such subpar development.} *

