1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} Bf5 4. Bd3 {This move isn't very well known, as it is not the most common approach in this position, but it is very interesting, and I believe that the ideas are very simple as well. I would absolutely recommend this for any time control, I think this is just a great move with simple play for White.} Bxd3 5. Qxd3 {At the moment, our threat is to push e5 - e6 and create weaknesses and development issues for Black.} e6 (5... Qa5+ {is a natural response, as the idea of trading queens is very well known, but it transposes to the e6 variation after, for example,} 6. c3 Qa6 7. Qd1 e6 8. Ne2 {.}) 6. Ne2 {It is important to know what White should do in this structure since Black has many options. Our first principle is to never trade the queen, and our idea is to place the b1 -knight on f3 with Nd2 - f3 and make the center solid with c3 . Afterwards, White will always pay attention to where the black knight on g8 goes. If it goes to f5 , the g2 - g4 push or the Ne2 - g3 trade may prove critical. Whenever a knight goes to g6 , it is a good idea to play g3 and h4 .} Nd7 {As White, we should be happy to see this move because Black has the option of putting the knight on c6 , where it is more active than on d7 . However, this is a very typical move in Caro-Kann structures, so I think it is very likely that this move will happen.} 7. O-O Ne7 8. c3 {Right now there are two moves: Nf5 and c5 , and in both cases, White's idea does not change much, as we follow our plan.} Nf5 {This is a logical move, but it is simply bad.} 9. Nd2 Be7 10. Nf3 {Following a simple plan is the best here.} O-O 11. g4 {A very strong move, and a key idea in these types of situations. There are many other good moves as well that keep the advantage, such as Kh1 and Bd2 , but all these moves are just prophylactic moves that are preparing g4 for in the future.} Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 {Currently, our threat is pushing g5 and trapping the black bishop on h4 , and we can later pick it up with Qh3 .} Be7 14. f5 {We have an extremely frightening attack coming up; Nf4 will follow, and Nh5 might also be an option at some point, as well as simple developing moves like Be3 or Rf3 - h3 .} *

