1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann is one of the most solid openings in the history of chess. Players who prefer a more solid and defensive style often choose the Caro-Kann, as it helps to avoid some of the sharp and tactical lines of other openings. The main idea is that no matter what White plays, Black's next move is an obvious one, and that is going to be ... d7 - d5 , challenging White's central pawn.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {By taking space right from the beginning, we can play the game in the best and most principled way.} Bf5 4. Bd3 {This move isn't very well known, as it is not the most common approach in this position, but it is very interesting, and I believe that the ideas are very simple as well. I would absolutely recommend this for any time control, I think this is just a great move with simple play for White.} Bxd3 5. Qxd3 {At the moment, our threat is to push e5 - e6 and create weaknesses and development issues for Black.} e6 (5... Qa5+ {is a natural response, as the idea of trading queens is very well known, but it transposes to the e6 variation after, for example,} 6. c3 Qa6 7. Qd1 e6 8. Ne2 {.}) 6. Ne2 {It is important to know what White should do in this structure since Black has many options. Our first principle is to never trade the queen, and our idea is to place the b1 -knight on f3 with Nd2 - f3 and make the center solid with c3 . Afterwards, White will always pay attention to where the black knight on g8 goes. If it goes to f5 , the g2 - g4 push or the Ne2 - g3 trade may prove critical. Whenever a knight goes to g6 , it is a good idea to play g3 and h4 .} c5 {My own experience and the database as well show that in this position ... c5 is the most natural and I believe the strongest move too. The main idea is to bring the knight to c6 .} 7. c3 {We need to make sure that our center is safe and we can capture on d4 with the c-pawn.} Nc6 8. O-O {Our ideas do not change. Again, we will try to bring the knight to the f3 -square and see where Black is going to put their knight, which is on g8 at the moment.} Nge7 {This is the most common approach, and I've faced this a lot during my blitz games as well.} 9. Nd2 Nf5 10. Nf3 Qb6 11. g4 {We follow our plan of moving the knight to h5 .} Nfe7 12. Nf4 Ng6 13. Nh5 {White's knight on h5 is extremely strong. First of all, it stops all the attacking ideas from Black's perspective, attacks the g7 -pawn, and delays Black's development. It is very likely that at some point Black is going to castle long, but then the a3 followed by b4 idea is very strong.} *

