their knight, which is on g8 at the moment.} Nge7 {This is the most common approach, and I've faced this a lot during my blitz games as well.} 9. Nd2 Nf5 10. Nf3 Be7 {This is definitely the most common way in online games as well as in over-the-board games.} 11. g4 {Now's the time! We have already achieved our favorite setup and it is time to push!} Nh4 ({After} 11... Nh6 12. h3 {, the h3 and g4 pawn structure is simply destroying the h6 -knight, and Ng3 followed by Nh5 is on the way, leaving Black with no hope.}) 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 {As always, f4 is part of the plan when we play g4 ; right now the threat is g5 , so we'll play Qh3 and trap the bishop, and another great idea is to push f5 and Nf4 .} Be7 14. f5 Qb6 {As well as keeping the game going, Black needs to be active to create counterplay, as otherwise, the attack simply ends up being fatal.} 15. Be3 O-O-O ({After} 15... Qxb2 16. Rab1 Qxa2 17. Rxb7 {, Black managed to win a pawn, but castling is not an option, and our attack is extremely strong.}) 16. Rab1 {Currently, we have complete control of the board, so if we wish to play aggressively, b4 is a good threat, but if we wish to win slowly, g5 and f6 would be a good choice.} *

