1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Bf5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 {An interesting position − usually, the trade of light-squared bishops is good for Black, but in this case, the position is concrete. Currently, Black has to stop Qb5 +.} Nc6 ({Normally, people who go for the 4...Bf5 line are aware of Qb5 +:} 6... Nf6 7. Qb5+ {.}) 7. O-O Bd6 {The best way to deal with Re1 +.} 8. Re1+ Nge7 9. Nc3 {Now Nxd5 is the threat.} O-O 10. Nb5 {White is trying to eliminate Black's strong dark-squared bishop.} Ng6 11. Nxd6 Qxd6 12. h4 Rfe8 13. Bd2 {It is important to always watch out for opportunities to make Qb5 and Qb3 types of moves in the future. White can also push g3 , Kg2 , then h5 followed by Bf4 .} *

