1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Bg4 {A common move I've encountered several times in online blitz games; this move is particularly tempting because it appears to be active, pinning the knight.} 5. h3 Bh5 6. Qe2+ {The idea is to have Qb5 + next, capturing the b7 -pawn.} Qe7 7. Be3 {We want to avoid trading queens. The idea behind Be3 is that White aims to develop with Nc3 and O-O-O , while also keeping the option of a future g4 and h4 advance.} Nc6 8. g4 Bg6 9. Nc3 {Attacking the d5 -pawn and preparing to castle queenside.} O-O-O 10. O-O-O Nf6 {This move seems very natural but is actually a blunder. It's important to cover this move to understand what White's real plan is after castling queenside.} 11. Ne5 {A very strong move, targeting the knight on c6 and preparing f4 to seize full control of the center. Capturing on e5 is not an option because, after f4 - f5 , White will win a piece.} *

