1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Nf6 {In this line, people tend to think White is not very ambitious, so Black is keeping the position symmetrical by making the same moves.} 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 {The idea of c3 is to make the d4 -pawn solid and to open the c2 -square for the bishop's retreat.} Nc6 ({After} 6... c4 7. Bc2 {, White's plan is quite straightforward: O-O , Re1 , Nbd2 - f1 - e3 , adding pressure on the d5 -pawn, while} Be7 {just loses a tempo in view of dxc5 .}) 7. O-O cxd4 {This move is intended to avoid getting isolated pawn positions.} 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. cxd4 Be7 10. Nc3 {The position is very symmetrical, and it looks like it is supposed to be equal, but White's pieces are much more active.} O-O 11. h3 {I like this move a lot, as it is very prophylactic. First of all, it stops ... Bg4 , and it also opens a window for White's king. Our next moves are going to be Bg5 or Bf4 .} Be6 12. Bf4 Rc8 13. Re1 {Both white bishops are better than Black's bishops. White's plan here is to keep developing with Qd2 and maybe even putting the bishop on e5 with the rook shift Re3 - g3 .} *

