1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Bd6 5. c4 {By avoiding all the symmetrical positions, this move keeps the game dynamic and sharp.} Nf6 {This is the main move, and it seems to me to be the most logical.} 6. c5 {I believe that this is the best move and the most challenging for Black. It leads to straightforward positions where Black has to play very carefully.} Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O {This is the main position of the line occurring after Nf6 , and here Black has to play b6 in order to attack White's strong c5 -pawn, as otherwise, Black would have spatial issues.} b6 9. Be3 {Quite a logical decision, White is trying to keep the space advantage.} bxc5 10. dxc5 a5 {The main idea is to stop the b2 - b4 push, which is logical and strong.} 11. Re1 {A very simple and developing move. There are many options here for Black, but our idea is very simple. We will try to keep the c5 -pawn protected, and our next moves are Nbd2 and Qc2 ; in the future, we can also try to push a3 and b4 .} *

