1. e4 e6 {The French Defense is a popular chess opening characterized by Black's early pawn move to e6 , which creates a solid and defensive pawn structure. The French Defense is known for leading to positions with asymmetrical pawn structures and imbalanced pawn formations.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 (3. exd5 {is a very interesting move. It has somewhat of a reputation among amateur players that this is a way of making a draw, but that is not the case. I do like this move because it avoids all the complications, and I believe that with good preparation, White can put pressure on Black.}) 3... exd5 4. Nf3 {Black has a lot of options here, but people usually tend to copy our moves with ... Nf6 and ... Bd6 .} Bd6 5. c4 {By avoiding all the symmetrical positions, this move keeps the game dynamic and sharp.} Nf6 {This is the main move, and it seems to me to be the most logical.} 6. c5 {I believe that this is the best move and the most challenging for Black. It leads to straightforward positions where Black has to play very carefully.} Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O {This is the main position of the line occurring after Nf6 , and here Black has to play b6 in order to attack White's strong c5 -pawn, as otherwise, Black would have spatial issues.} b6 9. Be3 {Quite a logical decision, White is trying to keep the space advantage.} bxc5 10. dxc5 Ng4 {This is a very direct approach to the game, attacking the bishop and forcing White to make an important decision.} 11. Bf4 {We need to keep the bishop and after Bf4 , Black is forced to capture our pawn, as otherwise, Qc2 and a3 followed by b4 would give us an enormous queenside space advantage.} (11. Bd4 $6 Nc6 {, keeping the bishop and not losing the pawn would be difficult.}) 11... Bxc5 12. Bxh7+ {A nice tactical resource.} Kxh7 13. Qc2+ Kg8 14. Qxc5 Na6 {Not so hard to find, but absolutely the only move to keep the game going.} 15. Qc6 {A mysterious maneuver at first sight, but by bringing the rook to b8 we slow down the implementation of ... c5 advances.} Rb8 16. Qc1 {Among White's ideas are Rd1 , Nbd2 , and Nb3 , as well as attacking the pawns on c7 and d5 .} *

