1. e4 d6 ({In contrast to the} 1... g6 {approach, there's a slightly different strategy at play in this scenario.}) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {We're staying on track with our strategy, progressing by executing Nf3 , then advancing the c3 -pawn, castling kingside, and fortifying our rook's position with Re1 . These moves align with our plan and set the stage for further strategic moves.} e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 g6 {Usually, Black aims to control the dark squares by placing the bishop on g7 .} 6. O-O Bg7 7. Bg5 {This move is quite effective in preventing the opponent's knight from moving, but our plan doesn't stop there. We're going to continue putting more pressure on that knight.} O-O 8. c3 {I find this approach to be optimal in this position. The pawns on b2 and c3 are indeed limiting the effectiveness of the g7 -bishop.} Nbd7 9. Nd2 Nc5 10. Bc2 {White's strategy in this position is wonderfully straightforward. The following ideas are refreshingly simple: start with Qe2 , reinforce the center with f4 , solidify the rook's position with Rae1 , and consider f4 - f5 or pivoting to an e4 - e5 breakthrough.} *

