1. e4 d6 ({In contrast to the} 1... g6 {approach, there's a slightly different strategy at play in this scenario.}) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {We're staying on track with our strategy, progressing by executing Nf3 , then advancing the c3 -pawn, castling kingside, and fortifying our rook's position with Re1 . These moves align with our plan and set the stage for further strategic moves.} e5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d5 {Attacking the knight and aiming to take full space in the center. We'll strengthen it with c4 next.} Ne7 6. c4 {This looks like a King's Indian Defense, but in this case, White is simply up too many tempi.} Ng6 7. Nc3 Be7 {So far, both sides are making logical, developing moves.} 8. h3 {Obviously, this is not the only move that gives an advantage, but this is an extremely strong prophylactic move that stops all the counterplay Black wants to create on the kingside with the ... f7 - f5 break.} O-O 9. g3 {A very strong move. The idea is to stop ... Nf4 penetrations in the future, and as you can see, the h3 -pawn is also limiting the c8 -bishop since now Black is unable to put the bishop on g4 or h3 .  If Black decides to go ... Ne8 with the idea to push ... f5 , we can stop that with Qc2 . Or an even better idea: by pushing h4 - h5 , we are making sure that the knight on g6 will have no other square but h8 , where it is obviously not placed very well. Now that White has stopped all the counterplay, it is very easy to continue the game plan with Be3 , b4 and c5 .} *

