1. e4 d6 ({In contrast to the} 1... g6 {approach, there's a slightly different strategy at play in this scenario.}) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {We're staying on track with our strategy, progressing by executing Nf3 , then advancing the c3 -pawn, castling kingside, and fortifying our rook's position with Re1 . These moves align with our plan and set the stage for further strategic moves.} e5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d5 {Attacking the knight and aiming to take full space in the center. We'll strengthen it with c4 next.} Nb4 {This move might seem unusual at first, but the idea is straightforward. Black reasons that White cannot move the bishop, as the e4 -pawn would be left unprotected. If White chooses not to move the bishop, Black is content to maintain the position, benefiting from the bishop pair advantage.} 6. Be2 ({A very clever solution. Black can't capture Nxe4 since after} 6. c3 {, White wins a piece. Black has to move the knight back to a6 and after Qa4 +, White is simply winning the knight on e4 .}) 6... a5 {This move ensures that the knight can go back to a6 and not be afraid of Bxa6 , which would ruin Black's pawn structure.} 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Nd2 {The idea of Nd2 is quite simple: the knight on c4 will be pretty strong and it will also create the threat of a3 followed by a capture on a5 .} O-O 9. Nc4 {White holds a clear and healthy advantage, with the main plan centered on queenside play. The next moves will be O-O , Be3 , and f3 , solidifying the position. From there, White can shift their full focus to executing the queenside strategy.} *

