1. e4 g6 2. d4 ({White continues with} 2. d4 {, reinforcing control over the center. Black's response} Bg7 {signifies the Modern Defense where Black delays pawn moves in favor of flexible piece development.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nf3 {White develops a knight and maintains a strong central presence.} c5 {The move ... c5 attacks White's center, forcing us to make an important decision.} 4. dxc5 ({Accepting the pawn is the best way to play here. Currently, Black has to try to get the pawn back as soon as possible. Otherwise, after} 4. c3 {and Be3 , White would be able to keep the pawn.}) 4... Qa5+ {The only way of getting the pawn back.} 5. c3 Qxc5 6. Na3 {A very strong move, planning to follow it up with Be3 and then later on to attack Black's queen again with Nb5 if it retreats to c7 .} d6 {A solid move. Here, we will stick to our plan and continue by targeting the black queen.} (6... Bxc3+ {is way too greedy, and after} 7. bxc3 Qxc3+ 8. Qd2 Qxa1 9. Nb5 Na6 10. Bc4 {followed by O-O , Black will sorely regret having ignored development. White is taking the initiative at a very fast pace, which more than compensates for the material investment; in fact, we have a +4 advantage on the engine's scale.}) 7. Be3 Qa5 8. e5 {First, we play e5 to stop ... Bxc3 + and force a direct capture on e5 , which leads to an unpleasant position for Black.} dxe5 9. Nb5 Nc6 10. b4 Qd8 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Ng5 Nh6 13. Bc4 {After all these forcing moves, White gains a huge advantage; f7 hangs, and after O-O-O , Black will struggle to survive.} *

