1. e4 g6 2. d4 ({White continues with} 2. d4 {, reinforcing control over the center. Black's response} Bg7 {signifies the Modern Defense where Black delays pawn moves in favor of flexible piece development.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nf3 {White develops a knight and maintains a strong central presence.} d6 {A very common move in the Modern Defense. Black maintains pawn flexibility for the forthcoming piece development.} 4. Bd3 {This is a reliable move that avoids unnecessary complications and ensures easy play in the middlegame.} Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 {Following the steps of 4.Bd3 . This is the main position that I recommend to play against the Pirc Defense, and we are going to take a look at the most common moves here.} Nc6 {Probably the best try for Black. As previously mentioned, ... e5 and ... c5 are the most common ideas here, so with ... Nc6 Black aims to go ... e5 and fight for the center.} 7. c3 {Following the main plan, defending the pawn, and making a useful move against ... e5 .} e5 8. h3 {Choosing to play h3 is a really smart move. It does two important things. First, it stops the ... Bg4 move, which could have made White's d4 -pawn weak. Second, it becomes strong when White plans to play Be3 followed by Nbd2 . This makes ... Ng4 not work anymore, and White can feel confident about controlling the center.} Nh5 {... Nh5 is a typical move in these types of positions, but here I believe that it is not as good as it seems.} 9. Be3 {Following the plan of creating a strong center.} f5 {The only logical continuation after Nh5 .} 10. exf5 gxf5 11. dxe5 {There is no need to be scared of Black's central pawns.} dxe5 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Bc4+ Kh8 14. Bc5 {Black has to give up the f8 -rook and the position is just hopeless.} *

