1. e4 g6 2. d4 ({White continues with} 2. d4 {, reinforcing control over the center. Black's response} Bg7 {signifies the Modern Defense where Black delays pawn moves in favor of flexible piece development.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nf3 {White develops a knight and maintains a strong central presence.} d6 {A very common move in the Modern Defense. Black maintains pawn flexibility for the forthcoming piece development.} 4. Bd3 {This is a reliable move that avoids unnecessary complications and ensures easy play in the middlegame.} Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 {Following the steps of 4.Bd3 . This is the main position that I recommend to play against the Pirc Defense, and we are going to take a look at the most common moves here.} Nc6 {Probably the best try for Black. As previously mentioned, ... e5 and ... c5 are the most common ideas here, so with ... Nc6 Black aims to go ... e5 and fight for the center.} 7. c3 {Following the main plan, defending the pawn, and making a useful move against ... e5 .} e5 8. h3 {Choosing to play h3 is a really smart move. It does two important things. First, it stops the ... Bg4 move, which could have made White's d4 -pawn weak. Second, it becomes strong when White plans to play Be3 followed by Nbd2 . This makes ... Ng4 not work anymore, and White can feel confident about controlling the center.} Re8 {One of the main moves, trying to keep the pressure in the center and stopping Be3 .} 9. Nbd2 {This is our usual move, and the next step is to shift the knight to g3 for better control of the center.} Nh5 {The only way to stop Nf1 - g3 is to play ... Nh5 , which attacks the d4 -pawn and aims to jump to f4 .} 10. d5 {With d5 , White is transposing to a King's Indian type of position. The rook on e8 is not standing as well as it was on f8 .} Ne7 11. c4 {It's going to be a bit surprising what White does next. We're planning to push the pawn from c4 to c5 , even if it means giving up that pawn. But the best part is that we'll have a really strong spot on c4 .  This might not seem like a great idea at first, but it's a positional pawn sacrifice to improve the position of our pieces. By putting a knight on c4 , White will dominate the board. Another idea can be Rb1 , b4 and c5 .} *

