1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 c6 ({This} 2... c6 {move has been suggested in some Chessable courses as an interesting attempt.}) 3. dxc6 {There is only one option that should be considered, and that is to accept the pawn sacrifice. Black has a small compensation, but it is not sufficient to equalize the game.} Nxc6 4. Nc3 e5 5. Bc4 {Simply developing is the best thing to do in this position. Even though Black controls the center, we are still ahead in development.} Nf6 6. Nge2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 {White is now a pawn up and the idea is very simple: White is always ready to trade pieces and simplify the position. You should watch out for when the time is right to make moves like Be3 or Bg5 , while Ng3 followed by Nce4 is always a good idea if you want to simplify the position and improve your knights.} *

