1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Nxd5 (3... Qxd5 {will transpose to Qxd5 .}) 4. c4 {This is quite similar to the Alekhine − when the knight is on d5 , it gets pushed away with c4 .} Nb6 5. Nf3 g6 6. h3 {Preventing ... Bg4 in the future.} Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 {Both sides are developing their pieces, but White is controlling the central squares.} Nc6 9. Be3 {White has achieved an ideal setup, with all the pawns properly defended. If the white pawn were not on h3 , Black's move ... Bg4 could become troublesome. In that case, the pawns on d4 and c4 could become vulnerable, especially after ... Bxf3 , which would put additional pressure on those pawns.} e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. g4 {This is a very strong move, dominating all of Black's counterplay. Now ... Nf5 is not an option anymore, and we plan to castle long and attack on the kingside.} f5 12. Qd2 {White holds a winning position according to the engines, which is understandable, as Black is devoid of counterplay. White plans to castle long, followed by either Bh6 to exchange Black's key defender, or c5 to break through on the queenside, solidifying the advantage.} *

