1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 ({This is one of the main moves, and I believe it is much stronger than} 5... Bg4 {. Black is trying to keep the bishop pair, develop all the pieces slowly, and stabilize the position.}) 6. Bd2 {A common and very strong move. In this position, we should play directly and put pressure on Black with every move.} c6 7. Ne4 {A direct and very interesting approach! It is not a common move, but a very strong one.} Qc7 ({If} 7... Qb6 {instead, after} 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 9. b4 e6 10. a3 Nd7 11. Be2 {, White is better.}) 8. Ng3 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 {Gaining the bishop pair advantage once again; the incoming ideas are Bc4 with O-O-O and Rhe1 .} *

