1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 ({This is one of the main moves, and I believe it is much stronger than} 5... Bg4 {. Black is trying to keep the bishop pair, develop all the pieces slowly, and stabilize the position.}) 6. Bd2 {A common and very strong move. In this position, we should play directly and put pressure on Black with every move.} e6 7. Ne5 {A little less common but also a very powerful move, creating the g4 and Nc4 threats.} Qb6 {Funnily enough, this is the only move that keeps the game alive.} 8. Qf3 Qxd4 9. Bb5+ {We will trade the knights and capture on b7 if Black covers our check with one of the knights.} c6 {Only move.} 10. Nxc6 {After this beautiful sacrifice, White is completely winning. After all the captures, the a8 -rook will be hanging and Black's position is hopeless.} *

