1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 ({This is one of the main moves, and I believe it is much stronger than} 5... Bg4 {. Black is trying to keep the bishop pair, develop all the pieces slowly, and stabilize the position.}) 6. Bd2 {A common and very strong move. In this position, we should play directly and put pressure on Black with every move.} e6 7. Ne5 {A little less common but also a very powerful move, creating the g4 and Nc4 threats.} Qb6 {Funnily enough, this is the only move that keeps the game alive.} 8. Qf3 c6 9. O-O-O {White's idea is to push g4 and h4 with the threat of h5 .} Nbd7 {Only move that stops g4 .} ({Following} 9... Qxd4 10. Bf4 {, it doesn't matter where the black queen goes, as g4 and h4 are White's next moves, and stopping h5 is impossible without creating major positional weaknesses. The position is hopeless for Black.}) 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {Here, the idea is to push f4 - f5 and create a weakness on e6 .} Be7 12. Qg3 {Now that Black is trying to finish development, soon we are going to utilize this fact and attack the g7 -pawn; ... O-O will be met with Bh6 , making it difficult for Black’s development to be satisfactorily completed.} *

