1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 ({This is one of the main moves, and I believe it is much stronger than} 5... Bg4 {. Black is trying to keep the bishop pair, develop all the pieces slowly, and stabilize the position.}) 6. Bd2 {A common and very strong move. In this position, we should play directly and put pressure on Black with every move.} e6 7. Ne5 {A little less common but also a very powerful move, creating the g4 and Nc4 threats.} Qb6 {Funnily enough, this is the only move that keeps the game alive.} 8. Qf3 Bxc2 {A very natural approach, which leads to a very straightforward line.} 9. Rc1 Bg6 10. Na4 {Forcing Black to capture another pawn.} Qxd4 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ {This is the only way to stop White from destroying Black's position completely. The a8 -rook is hanging, and Qc8 + or Bb5 + is very close to being mate, so trading queens is the only option for Black to save the game.} 13. Qxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxc7 Nxd2 {Black should take on d2 to eliminate the bishop pair advantage and finish development with a tempo.} 15. Kxd2 Bb4+ 16. Kc2 O-O 17. Be2 {Black is still struggling with development; right now Bf3 is a huge threat, and our rook will join the game via d1 .} *

