1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This is the oldest approach used in the Scandinavian. Black's ideas are pretty simple: ... Nf6 , ... c6 , and later developing the light-squared bishop. Also, ... c6 gives the queen a square to return to.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 {... Bg4 is a very common move in these types of positions. Black usually tries to give up the pair of bishops and create a solid center with the e6 and c6 -pawns.} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bd2 {Bd2 is almost always happening after Qa5 , as it stops the pin and also in the future can be useful for ideas such as Ne4 .} Nbd7 {A good and healthy development move, while an early ... e6 can cause problems due to Ne4 .} 9. g4 {It is difficult to break through in this type of position if Black has time to consolidate, but in this case, Black doesn't have the time to do so.  The main point of this move is to force the knight out from the f6 -square; later on, White will occupy the e4 -square with the knight, and with c4 we'll try to push the black knight away from d5 and create a powerful center.} e6 10. g5 Nd5 11. Ne4 {Following the idea.} Qb6 {This is definitely the most natural move, but not the best, and leads to a losing position.} 12. O-O-O {It is very common for White to sacrifice the d4 -pawn in the Scandinavian, and here too, White's attack is very strong. There are no good moves for Black; c4 , and Bc3 are extremely powerful. White will take the center and with h4 and h5 , Black's position will become hopeless.} ({And if after Qxd4} 12. c4 {, Black tries} Nc5 {, the strong} 13. g6 $1 hxg6 14. Ng5 {will keep White on the good side of the complications.}) *

