{This is the most powerful response against g6 , but obviously trying to castle kingside is also a decent choice.  In this case, White's attack is extremely powerful and yet simple at the same time. Opening up the h-file is the main goal, and with Bh6 followed by h4 - h5 White is able to successfully achieve this goal.} 1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 ({It is less common to play the Scandinavian with} 3... Qd8 {. I think it's an interesting and solid option and the main idea of Qd8 is that, unlike Qa5 and Qd6 , Black's queen is not getting attacked by White's minor pieces.}) 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 {The main idea of ... g6 is to fianchetto both bishops; on g7 and in due course, if White castles short, on b7 .} 6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O *

