1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {The modern approach of the Scandinavian is probably the best try. Black's main idea is to keep the queen in the center of the board while keeping it active.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nge2 {This move isn't the most popular in this situation, but it has a very simple idea: White wants to attack the queen with Bf4 and get ahead in development.} a6 {A second logical response by Black; playing ... b5 and ... Bb7 in the future is the plan.} 6. Bf4 Qd8 7. g3 {A very strong developing move that also stops Black's main idea of pushing ... b7 - b5 .} Bf5 {Black has to try to develop the c8 -bishop, as otherwise, the bishop would stay there for a very long time, having no activity whatsoever.} 8. Bg2 c6 9. d5 {Black would achieve a solid center if ... e6 was allowed. We must ensure that the g2 -bishop is active, and our only option for opening the h1 - a8 diagonal is to play d5 .} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 {Only move to stop Nc7 +.} 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxd5 Nc6 13. O-O-O {White is ahead in development and that gives us an edge; it is important to bring the last piece into the game with Rhe1 .} *

