1. e4 d5 {This opening is referred to as the Scandinavian Defense or Scandinavian Opening. It is one of the oldest openings in the history of chess and also one of Magnus Carlsen's favorite openings in his blitz repertoire. Black initiates the game by opening up the position and forcing an open, dynamic battle.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {The modern approach of the Scandinavian is probably the best try. Black's main idea is to keep the queen in the center of the board while keeping it active.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nge2 {This move isn't the most popular in this situation, but it has a very simple idea: White wants to attack the queen with Bf4 and get ahead in development.} c6 {Black wants to keep it solid and have the options of the c8 -bishop open.} 6. Bf4 Qd8 7. Qd2 {Right now, we are following the main idea behind 5.Nge2 , which is to castle long.} Bf5 8. O-O-O e6 9. Ng3 {White attacks the f5 -bishop and gains another important tempo, which is the key idea of Nge2 .} Bg6 10. h4 h6 11. h5 Bh7 12. Bd3 {Trading bishops is a good idea that also sets up a nice trap. The main goal of trading bishops is to control the center with Nge4 and launch an attack with Qg3 or g4 .} Bxd3 (12... Qxd4 {, it is always tempting to get free pawns, but in this case, it would cost Black the game.} 13. Nb5 $3 {and it is impossible for Black to stop Nc7 , as capturing the knight would also result in the loss of the queen.}) 13. Qxd3 Nbd7 14. Nge4 {In this position, White has full control of the center. If Black moves the bishop to e7 or b4 , Qg3 is always very strong; Nd6 + and a g4 -pawn sacrifice are also important ideas to consider.} *

