1. e4 Nc6 (1... Nc6 {is an uncommon chess opening known as the Nimzowitsch Defense. The flexibility of this move allows for creative play and can lead to unexpected, unique, and unknown positions on the board.}) 2. Nf3 d5 {An interesting move − it is an attempt to get some sort of Scandinavian, but the knight on c6 is placed really badly.} (2... e5 {would transpose to the 1...e5 move order .}) ({is an interesting move order, trying to achieve a Modern Defense: d4} 2... d6 3. Bd3 {Bg7 c3 , and we transposed .}) 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5 5. Bb5 {The idea is to play Ne5 or d4 - d5 .} Bd7 {Stopping Ne5 .} 6. d4 a6 {The only way to stop d5 temporarily and keep hopes for ... Bg4 .} 7. Bc4 O-O-O (7... Bg4 {would run into a pretty tactic:} 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. d5 $1 {, preparing Ng5 + next, as playing Ng5+ directly is ill-advised in view of Qxg5 .}) 8. h3 {A very important and strong move, stopping ... Bg4 and keeping Bxf7 as a threat. Black is simply unable to create any activity; at some point, playing ... e6 will be necessary, and that will keep the black bishop and rook on d8 passive.} *

