1. e4 Nc6 (1... Nc6 {is an uncommon chess opening known as the Nimzowitsch Defense. The flexibility of this move allows for creative play and can lead to unexpected, unique, and unknown positions on the board.}) 2. Nf3 d6 (2... e5 {would transpose to the 1...e5 move order .}) ({is an interesting move order, trying to achieve a Modern Defense: d4} 2... d6 3. Bd3 {Bg7 c3 , and we transposed .}) 3. d4 {Now it is the time to seize the center!} Bg4 {This is the most common move that occurs in online games. The idea is to pin the knight, and Black also wants to take on f3 and damage the pawn structure.} 4. d5 Ne5 {The most common move in this position, which is a blunder.} 5. Nxe5 {This is a very beautiful queen sacrifice, but it is temporary since we will get it back.} Bxd1 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 {Here, the threats are cxb7 + or c7 + and the only way not to lose the queen is to give a check on a5 .} Qa5+ 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Nc4 Qc7 (9... Qb4 10. a3 Qc5 11. Be3 Qh5 12. Rxd1 {, or cxb7 first, is also bad for Black.}) 10. Nd5 {Black's queen is trapped, and since we are ahead in development, White is completely winning.} ({Qb8 doesn't help. After c7 Qa8 , the ruthless engine doesn't even want to take the bishop on d1 followed by a check on b6 , which is also winning. Instead,} 10. Bd2 {is even stronger, with the idea of Ba5 and mate on d8 next.}) *

