1. e4 Nc6 (1... Nc6 {is an uncommon chess opening known as the Nimzowitsch Defense. The flexibility of this move allows for creative play and can lead to unexpected, unique, and unknown positions on the board.}) 2. Nf3 d6 (2... e5 {would transpose to the 1...e5 move order .}) ({is an interesting move order, trying to achieve a Modern Defense: d4} 2... d6 3. Bd3 {Bg7 c3 , and we transposed .}) 3. d4 {Now it is the time to seize the center!} Nf6 4. Bb5 ({The most important thing in a blitz game is to get positions in which the ideas are simple, and} 4. Bb5 {gives White a clear advantage. It is also a relatively new move − the main move is Nc3 .}) 4... Bd7 (4... Nxe4 $4 5. d5 a6 6. Bd3 {and Black is losing a piece.}) 5. Nc3 {Now e5 is a threat that Black should try to neutralize with a6 .} a6 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. d5 Bd7 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 {Although Black has the bishop pair, White is far ahead in development, and with O-O , Qf3 , and Bg5 next, White is in good shape.} *

