1. e4 Nc6 (1... Nc6 {is an uncommon chess opening known as the Nimzowitsch Defense. The flexibility of this move allows for creative play and can lead to unexpected, unique, and unknown positions on the board.}) 2. Nf3 d6 (2... e5 {would transpose to the 1...e5 move order .}) ({is an interesting move order, trying to achieve a Modern Defense: d4} 2... d6 3. Bd3 {Bg7 c3 , and we transposed .}) 3. d4 {Now it is the time to seize the center!} Nf6 4. Bb5 ({The most important thing in a blitz game is to get positions in which the ideas are simple, and} 4. Bb5 {gives White a clear advantage. It is also a relatively new move − the main move is Nc3 .}) 4... a6 ({In this position, the most popular move is} 4... a6 {, where Black is trying to get the bishop pair advantage. Instead, Nxe4??} 5. d5 {a6 Bd3+- and Black is losing a piece.}) 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nbd2 e6 {It is natural to develop the bishop on e7 , but the e7 and c8 -squares are very limited and offer little scope in this case.} (6... Bg4 {is a common move among club-level players; the idea is to pin the knight, but it is not very good in this case.} 7. c4 {− we want to bring the queen to a4 and attack the c6 -pawn, proving that the bishop on g4 is misplaced.}) 7. O-O Be7 8. c4 O-O 9. Qc2 {White has full control over the center, and it will be even better after b3 followed by Bb2 .} ({We can also consider the c5 idea. For instance, after Nd7} 9. c5 {and if} dxc5 10. Nc4 {, White develops a fast initiative in return. If you are not up for an adventure, Nb3 , preventing ... c5 and preparing c5 , is also a good way to preserve the slight plus we have in this position.}) *

