1. e4 Nf6 (1... Nf6 {, known as Alekhine's Defense, is not the most common move, but it leads to interesting and sharp positions. With Nf6 , Black is provoking White to take the center right from the start of the game.}) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 {We are now at the point when we need to decide whether to play f4 , which leads to a very sharp game, or to play the text move exd6 , which leads to a more positional game.} 5. exd6 cxd6 (5... exd6 {leads to a symmetrical position, which is usually easier to play as White, whereas cxd6 changes the pawn structure and makes the position more difficult to play.}) 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4 ({The move} 7. a4 {is extremely strong, and it provides a good surprise element since there aren't any high-level games here.}) 7... Bg7 {The most common move in this position allows White to push the knight on b6 aside.} 8. a5 N6d7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Be2 Nc6 11. d5 {Black must play extremely carefully to avoid losing the game immediately after this strong move.} Bxc3+ (11... Nxa5 12. Ra3 {and Black's knight is trapped.}) 12. bxc3 Nxa5 13. Bh6 Re8 14. h4 Nf6 (14... Nf6 {is obviously the most logical and the best move in the position, but it doesn't stop White from pushing} 15. h5 {.}) 15. h5 b6 ({In case of} 15... Nxh5 16. Rxh5 gxh5 17. Ng5 {, the incoming attack with moves such as Bd3 , Qd3 , and Bh5 is just deadly for Black.}) 16. hxg6 fxg6 17. Ng5 {White's pieces are much better coordinated and the attack is still there. We should always be on the lookout for sacrifices like Nxh7 , following up with Bd3 . This position is practically winning for White.} *

