1. e4 Nf6 (1... Nf6 {, known as Alekhine's Defense, is not the most common move, but it leads to interesting and sharp positions. With Nf6 , Black is provoking White to take the center right from the start of the game.}) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 {We are now at the point when we need to decide whether to play f4 , which leads to a very sharp game, or to play the text move exd6 , which leads to a more positional game.} 5. exd6 cxd6 (5... exd6 {leads to a symmetrical position, which is usually easier to play as White, whereas cxd6 changes the pawn structure and makes the position more difficult to play.}) 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4 ({The move} 7. a4 {is extremely strong, and it provides a good surprise element since there aren't any high-level games here.}) 7... a5 {The second most common move, but the best according to the engines.} 8. c5 {The straightforward approach leads to a very complex position where Black must find many accurate moves in order not to lose the game immediately.} dxc5 9. Bb5+ N6d7 ({The only move that does not lose immediately.} 9... Nc6 10. d5 {and White stays a piece up.}) 10. Bg5 {We are choosing an aggressive approach, sacrificing a pawn, but the piece activity is more important in this case.} Bg7 {This move is very logical, and obviously the most natural one, but it is losing!} 11. Nd5 f6 {Only move.} 12. Be3 cxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O 14. Rd1 {As White is down a pawn, piece activity plays an important role here. The bishop on the b5 -square has great power, the rook on d1 is attacking the knight on d7 and pins the queen. Black has some weaknesses too, such as the e6 and b6 -squares.} *

