1. e4 Nf6 (1... Nf6 {, known as Alekhine's Defense, is not the most common move, but it leads to interesting and sharp positions. With Nf6 , Black is provoking White to take the center right from the start of the game.}) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 {We are now at the point when we need to decide whether to play f4 , which leads to a very sharp game, or to play the text move exd6 , which leads to a more positional game.} 5. exd6 cxd6 (5... exd6 {leads to a symmetrical position, which is usually easier to play as White, whereas cxd6 changes the pawn structure and makes the position more difficult to play.}) 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4 ({The move} 7. a4 {is extremely strong, and it provides a good surprise element since there aren't any high-level games here.}) 7... a5 {The second most common move, but the best according to the engines.} 8. c5 {The straightforward approach leads to a very complex position where Black must find many accurate moves in order not to lose the game immediately.} dxc5 9. Bb5+ N6d7 ({The only move that does not lose immediately.} 9... Nc6 10. d5 {and White stays a piece up.}) 10. Bg5 {We are choosing an aggressive approach, sacrificing a pawn, but the piece activity is more important in this case.} h6 11. Bh4 Nc6 12. d5 Nd4 {This is the only way for Black to stay in the game.} 13. d6 g5 {Black has to get rid of the pin, as otherwise, the position is hopeless.} 14. Bg3 Bg7 {A very natural move, especially in a blitz game, which is losing right after Nd5 .} 15. Nd5 exd6 16. Bxd6 {The unstoppable threats are Nc7 , Bc7 , and Be7 .} *

