1. e4 Nf6 (1... Nf6 {, known as Alekhine's Defense, is not the most common move, but it leads to interesting and sharp positions. With Nf6 , Black is provoking White to take the center right from the start of the game.}) 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 {We are now at the point when we need to decide whether to play f4 , which leads to a very sharp game, or to play the text move exd6 , which leads to a more positional game.} 5. exd6 cxd6 (5... exd6 {leads to a symmetrical position, which is usually easier to play as White, whereas cxd6 changes the pawn structure and makes the position more difficult to play.}) 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4 ({The move} 7. a4 {is extremely strong, and it provides a good surprise element since there aren't any high-level games here.}) 7... a5 {The second most common move, but the best according to the engines.} 8. c5 {The straightforward approach leads to a very complex position where Black must find many accurate moves in order not to lose the game immediately.} dxc5 9. Bb5+ N6d7 ({The only move that does not lose immediately.} 9... Nc6 10. d5 {and White stays a piece up.}) 10. Bg5 {We are choosing an aggressive approach, sacrificing a pawn, but the piece activity is more important in this case.} h6 11. Bh4 Nc6 12. d5 Nd4 {This is the only way for Black to stay in the game.} 13. d6 g5 {Black has to get rid of the pin, as otherwise, the position is hopeless.} 14. Bg3 exd6 15. Nf3 Nxb5 16. Nxb5 Nf6 {Black is surviving. I believe that it is very difficult for White to know what to do in this position, as it looks extremely dangerous. However, White has a lot of options to continue the game, and a lot of them are looking very good and close to winning.} 17. O-O Be6 18. Re1 Be7 {The best move according to the engine.} 19. Nxd6+ Kf8 20. Ra3 {Bringing the rook into the game.} c4 {The only move, stopping the powerful Rd3 .} 21. Re2 Ra6 22. Rd2 Nd5 {A playable position for Black can only be maintained by this move.} 23. Nxc4 Bxa3 24. bxa3 {Obviously, for Black, it is almost impossible to find all these moves. Even if Black manages to find them all, this position is very playable, and it's still very hard for Black to find the correct moves to equalize.   The main ideas for White are to play on the dark squares, use the pin with Ne3 , and watch out for the right time to make moves like Be5 , Nd4 , or Nfe5 .} *

