1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nd5 {Since this move is relatively fresh and I am the only one who is playing it regularly, I had to choose one of my own games. :)} Be7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. c3 d6 7. Bc2 Be6 ({As you probably already have seen, the main move here is} 7... Nxd5 {, but Be6 is extremely natural.}) 8. Nxe7+ Qxe7 9. O-O Rad8 ({9…d5 is the move covered in the course, and} 9... Rad8 {is clearly aiming to play ... d6 - d5 , so White's plan does not change.}) 10. d4 d5 11. dxe5 Nxe4 12. Nd4 {The key move!} Nxe5 13. f3 Nf6 14. Re1 Nc6 {Although it is odd and difficult to explain why White sacrificed a complete pawn at this point,  the following moves will make it obvious.} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qd4 {Considering that Qh4 and Bg5 are basically unstoppable, I really loved making this move in the game. It's one of my favorite lines in the course.} c5 17. Qh4 d4 {A huge mistake, but it was already too late to do anything about it.} (17... h6 {is the move that simultaneously prevents Bxh7 + and Bg5 , but does not keep Black alive.} 18. Bxh6 gxh6 19. Qxh6 {and Re5 is impossible to stop. White is completely winning.}) 18. Bxh7+ {Nice trick; it was only a matter of skill after this move.} Kh8 19. Bg5 Rfe8 20. Re5 d3 21. Bxd3+ Kg8 22. Bh7+ Kf8 23. Rae1 Rb8 24. Bc2 Kg8 25. b3 c4 26. b4 Red8 27. Bh7+ Kf8 28. Bf5 Qd6 29. Qh8+ Ke7 30. Qxg7 *

