1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 6. c3 Nd7 7. Ne2 c5 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nd2 Nc6 10. Qg3 {A powerful move played by Demchenko! This move has also been covered in the course . It is important not to go Nf3 very early in this case.} ({The idea of} 10. Qg3 {is very simple: we are stopping Black from castling kingside, when it is hard for Black to develop logically with ... Be7 since the g7 -pawn is hanging. Moreover, ... g7 - g6 would weaken the dark squares, and after Nf3 , our c1 -bishop would become very powerful.}) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 g6 {A logical move. Black wants to castle as soon as possible, and for that reason, they want to make sure that the g7 -pawn is not hanging.} 12. Nf3 {Opening up the bishop and preparing Bg5 or Bh6 in case of ... Be7 .} h6 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Bc3 Bb4 15. Bxb4 Qxb4 16. b3 O-O-O {This is a logical way of playing for Black. All of our pieces are directed towards the kingside, and that's why many players with Black are trying to avoid and escape by castling queenside.} 17. Qf4 Qe7 18. Qd2 Kb8 19. Ne1 {A strong idea, bringing the knight to d3 and preparing f4 and jumping with the knight to c5 .} Rc8 20. Nd3 Qg5 21. f4 Qf5 22. h3 Qh5 23. Qe1 f5 24. exf6 Nxf6 25. Ng3 Qh4 26. Rd1 Rhe8 27. Qe3 Nd7 28. Ne2 Re7 29. Rc1 g5 30. b4 Nb6 31. Ne5 gxf4 32. Nxf4 Qg5 33. h4 Qg8 34. Nfg6 Rg7 35. h5 Nxb4 36. Rxc8+ Qxc8 37. Rf8 *

