1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. c4 dxc4 6. Bxc4 Nf6 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Bxe7 9. Nc3 {Following Qe2 +, this is the main position that appears. White usually has the advantage here because we are ahead in development.} c6 {This is one of the ways of stopping Nb5 . Black also wants to control the d5 -square and prepare ... Bd6 in the future.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bd6 12. Bg5 {White is ahead in development. Now the idea is to take on f6 and damage Black's pawn structure.} Nbd7 13. Bb3 {A smart move, with the idea to stop ... Nb6 with tempo followed by ... Nfd5 .} h6 14. Bh4 Re8 15. Rxe8+ Nxe8 16. Re1 Kf8 17. a3 {White is still ahead in development, and Black has to decide how to bring the c8 -bishop and the a8 -rook into the game.} f6 18. Ne4 Be7 19. Bg3 {Preparing Nh4 and stopping ... Nd6 .} g5 20. Nc3 Nb6 21. d5 Bd7 22. Nd4 Bc5 23. dxc6 Bxd4 {Black collapsed here.} (23... bxc6 {would have still kept some hopes alive, but it does not give equality. After} 24. Ne6+ Bxe6 25. Rxe6 {, White has a huge advantage. The two bishops are pretty strong, and the c6 and f6 -pawns are weak.}) 24. cxb7 *

