1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O {This is the most powerful response against 5...g6 . Obviously, trying to castle kingside is a decent choice, but in this case, White's attack is extremely powerful and simple at the same time. Opening up the h-file is the main goal, and with Bh6 followed by h4 - h5 , White is able to achieve this goal.} a6 9. Bh6 {Andreikin is following the game plan.} b5 10. Bxg7 ({I would personally prefer} 10. h4 {, but this move is also great.}) 10... Kxg7 11. h4 Bg4 12. h5 {A very strong move. We do not need the h-pawn for the attack, we just need to open the h-file.} Bxh5 13. Be2 b4 14. Na4 Qd5 15. c4 bxc3 16. Nxc3 Qa5 17. Ne5 {And now White is opening up the h-file, as g4 is the threat.} Bxe2 18. Qh6+ Kg8 19. Nxe2 {White is completely winning; it is impossible to stop Nc3 - e4 or Ng4 .} Qxa2 20. Nc3 Qe6 21. Ne4 Re8 22. Ng5 Qf5 23. Nxh7 Nbd7 24. Nxf6+ Qxf6 25. Qh7+ Kf8 26. Nxd7# {A very beautiful and instructive game by Andreikin.} *

